<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth poll finds Clinton-Lazio race tight  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A fourth statewide poll in less than three
weeks has found Hillary Rodham Clinton in a very close Senate race
with Republican Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News/New York Times poll released Monday had Clinton with
a slight lead over the congressman from Long Island. The first lady
was backed by 44 percent of likely voters surveyed to 39 percent
for Lazio. Seventeen percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News/New York Times poll out in April had Clinton leading
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, 49 percent to 41 percent, with 10 percent
undecided. Giuliani quit the race May 19 to deal with his prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that in many ways the Senate race has become a
whole new contest with Lazio replacing Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the number of undecided voters increased, but
while Clinton and Giuliani were running even in traditionally more
conservative upstate New York in April, the new poll had Lazio
leading in that region, 46 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in the category of who would be better at working with other
senators, Clinton's edge has largely evaporated. In April, Clinton
led Giuliani, 57 percent to 30 percent, on that front. In the new
poll, 42 percent said Clinton would work better with other senators
while 38 percent said that about Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   While 30 percent of voters said Lazio was spending more time
attacking Clinton than talking about issues, 52 percent said that
was the case with Giuliani back in April.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed is that many New Yorkers would
prefer to have a senator who was born in the state. Almost four in
10 voters in the new poll felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has been stressing the carpetbagger issue, presenting
himself as the ''Made in New York'' candidate. Until January,
Clinton has never lived in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll also found that many voters really don't know much
about the new Republican candidate. Forty-seven percent said they
didn't know enough about Lazio to even decide if their impression
of him was favorable or unfavorable. Twenty-six percent said they
had a favorable opinion of him while 10 percent said they had an
unfavorable opinion of the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 1,187 likely voters was conducted from
June 4 through Saturday and had a margin of error of three
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lazio joined the race, polls have either shown Clinton
with a small lead or the two candidates essentially tied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 0001 </TRAILER>
