<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Overturns On Interstate; 1 Dead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENFIELD, Ind. (AP) -- A sport-utility vehicle crossed a
highway median Monday and collided with a Greyhound bus, flipping
the bus onto its side. One person was killed and more than 40
others were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw the SUV coming across the median. The bus driver tried
to veer to the right to get out of the way,' said Todd Turpin, who
was driving behind the bus. ''But there was nothing he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident, about 25 miles east of Indianapolis, happened
during afternoon rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the sport-utility vehicle was killed, said Hancock
County Sheriff Nick Gulling. She was identified as Amy
McKee-Everett, 31, of rural Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Clarke Mercer said all 45 passengers were injured,
along with the bus' driver, Julian Stenger of Indianapolis. Two
people were in fair condition, but none of the injuries appeared
life threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The bus was headed from New York to Los Angeles and had most
recently stopped in Dayton, Ohio, Greyhound spokeswoman Kristin
Parsley said. It was scheduled to stop in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Police closed both lanes of the highway near the crash.
Passengers sat in a field as rescue workers tended to the injured
near the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Truck driver Rick Tucker, 39, of Whitley City, Ky., said he saw
the accident and he described passengers jumping out the windows of
the wrecked bus. Someone brought a ladder to the scene so others
could leave the bus through an escape hatch on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just thankful it didn't kill any of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1914, Greyhound Lines Inc. is the only national bus
line in the United States, serving 2,600 destinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
