<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad Gave Syria Stability  </HEADLINE>
By HAMZA HENDAWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Hafez Assad will be remembered most for
giving Syria what it desperately needed: stability. But it came at
a tremendous cost to his country.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Assad seized power in a 1970 coup, Syria had
experienced the turmoil of at least 20 military coups since
independence from France 24 years earlier, making the country the
butt of jokes in the Arab world and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A Soviet-trained air force pilot and a shrewd politician, Assad
held the country together for 30 years with sheer force of will and
occasional outbursts of brutality. His zero tolerance for dissent
meant the jailing or killing of thousands of Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfalls of the Assad years were obvious -- human-rights
abuses, a moribund economy. But also apparent was the pride of a
nation that sees itself as the last flag-bearer of Arabism.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a virtually total absence of democracy, Assad left this
country of 17 million people in an economic time warp, symbolized
by the cars dating from the 1970s that ply the streets of the
capital. Decades of massive defense spending in a country lacking
many basic services contributed to the economic lag.
</P>
<P>
   The average monthly salary of a university graduate in Syria
today is a meager $60. The number of Syrians who have mobile
telephones is only about 4,000 -- not surprising, since it costs
about $1,500 to rent a line and buy a set. Per capita gross
domestic product shrank to a modest $837 in 1997 from $1,045 in
1995, according to figures released last year by the U.S.
Department of Commerce. More recent figures were not available.
</P>
<P>
   The country does not have a stock exchange, and widespread
corruption is eating into its resources. Foreign investment remains
below expectations and a 1991 law that relaxed investment
regulations has failed to bring about any real results.
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew by an average 5 percent in the years 1991-96,
but shrank in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The economy -- like everything else in Assad's Syria -- always
trailed the struggle against Israel on the list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Syria opened peace talks with Israel following the 1991 peace
conference in Madrid, but has since made little progress toward a
treaty. Throughout on-again and off-again negotiations since, Assad
had insisted on nothing short of the return of the entire Golan
Heights, captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   His decision not to lead his negotiators in person, leaving the
task to Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa -- won him plaudits at
home, but generated unease abroad as a display of the contempt he
obviously felt for his enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Such hard-line policies, though viewed with concern abroad, have
long been a source of pride to ordinary Syrians. Although desperate
for the so-called peace dividend they hope would come with a treaty
with Israel, they saw their country -- and Assad -- as steadfast and
unyielding.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of pride, however misplaced, was a constant theme in
the information machine that surrounded Assad. Editorials and
official statements are peppered with phrases such as ''Syria is
the heart of the Arab world.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Assad's son and heir apparent, Bashar Assad, may find it
difficult to make concessions to reach a peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bashar has a heavy legacy left for him by his father: 'Not a
single inch of territory to be conceded.' It is a huge motto which
only someone like Assad the father, with all his abilities and
legitimacy, could uphold,'' said Hassan Abu Taleb, an Arab affairs
expert at Cairo's Al-Ahram Center for Political and Strategic
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Any resumption of peace talks now may have to wait until the
34-year-old Bashar, who was groomed by his father to take power but
has little political base of his own, finds his feet as the new
leader.
</P>
<P>
   So wrapped up has Syria been in its conflict with Israel -- with
which it fought three full-fledged wars since 1948 -- that Hafez
Assad's Syria, with all its dreams of glory, in the end became a
backwater, largely forgotten by the outside world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 0112 </TRAILER>
