<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Seek Action After UN Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Armed with renewed backing from more than
180 nations and an updated plan to achieve equality of the sexes,
thousands of participants are returning home from a U.N. women's
conference determined to stop making speeches and start taking
action.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the largest global gathering of women in
history, the nations of the world met to review the landmark
150-page platform for action that they adopted in Beijing. They not
only gave it a thumbs up but added some tougher measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''Member states in the United Nations system now have a clearly
defined roadmap for the continuing journey toward gender
equality,'' Assistant Secretary-General Angela King, the U.N.
special adviser on gender issues, said Monday. ''The will to act
was demonstrated by governments.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to new measures to combat domestic violence, sex
trafficking and the impact of globalization on women. ''The women
of the world now have a tool to assist them in achieving their
goals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting more than 180 nations to reach consensus on an updated
roadmap was a long and difficult process. The weeklong special
session of the General Assembly, scheduled to end Friday, didn't
finish until Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   There was relief from Secretary-General Kofi Annan and dozens of
governments, including the United States, which feared that the
conference would backtrack on Beijing's gains for women.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most wonderful thing is that there's no sliding back,''
said Noeleen Heyzer, executive director of the United Nations
Development Fund for Women. ''It is extremely important now that we
go from words into action.''
</P>
<P>
   She called for greater accountability to achieve equality in
education, jobs and decision-making. She urged governments and the
private sector to earmark more money to implement the Beijing
platform. And she said the U.N. agency ''will support as many
governments as possible'' in reviewing laws that discriminate
against women by 2005, as called for by last week's conference.
</P>
<P>
   The new document notes that the Convention on the Elimination of
Discrimination Against Women -- the legal cornerstone of women's
equality -- has been signed by 165 nations but failed to achieve the
goal of universal ratification by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference, Saudi Arabia announced that it would sign
the convention and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
the Clinton administration had intensified efforts to get the
Senate to ratify it.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines for last week's conference -- known as Beijing
Plus Five -- mirrored those at Beijing: the Vatican and a handful of
Islamic and Catholic countries -- including Libya, Algeria, Iran,
Sudan and Nicaragua -- against the West and thousands of women's
rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   As at Beijing, the most contentious issues dealt with sexual and
reproductive issues.
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Germain, president of the International Women's Health
Coalition and a member of the U.S. delegation to Beijing, said
Monday that one major achievement last week was ''a real
obstruction of the right-wing effort to take us backward.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to the follow-up document's support for education
programs and services on reproductive and sexual health for
adolescents and a restatement of language urging governments to
review laws that punish women for having abortions and its
references to sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ''So it's clear now that sexuality, like gender, is an issue
that governments cannot deny or ignore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What voluntary organizations are committed to now, Germain said,
''is developing innovative projects that can show governments how
to change policies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problems that women face at the start of the 21st
century were graphically recounted as the conference closed, a
reminder to those returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates from embattled Sierra Leone and Congo said they were
missing the key prerequisite to implement the Beijing platform:
peace. Africans spoke of the AIDS pandemic destroying the social
fabric of the continent. Asians spoke about the financial crisis
leaving women without enough to eat and an upsurge in trafficking,
forced prostitution and so-called honor killings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
