<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Nuclear Secrets Missing  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Investigators are intensely looking for two
computer hard drives, containing nuclear weapons secrets,
discovered missing from a vault at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico. The incident is prompting renewed
questions in Congress over security at the federal research labs.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the nuclear weapons data was discovered
more than a month ago, but was not made known to senior Energy
Department officials until June 1. It was disclosed publicly Monday
after a weeklong investigation by three dozen FBI and Energy
Department agents who swept down on the lab.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very sensitive ... technical data,'' retired Air Force
Gen. Eugene Habiger, the Energy Department's security chief, said.
He briefed Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Monday on the
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The drives were found missing May 7 as the lab was threatened by
wildfires that forced an evacuation three days later, officials
said. The two drives may have been misplaced or accidentally
destroyed in the confusion surrounding the oncoming fire that
burned thousands of acres in and around Los Alamos, N.M., including
some of the laboratory, last month.
</P>
<P>
   Habiger was expected to be questioned on the missing nuclear
secrets at a House Commerce Committee hearing today. The House
Intelligence Committee was considering hearings later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Senior DOE officials, however, expressed doubt that the
disappearance of the two hard drives -- each just a little larger
than a deck of cards -- involves espionage, although they have not
ruled it out completely.
</P>
<P>
   ''The indicators are just not there,'' said Ed Curran, DOE's
director of counterintelligence. Still, he said everyone with
access to the material or vault will be given a polygraph.
</P>
<P>
   The two drives, each containing identical information, were used
by the Nuclear Emergency Search Team, or NEST, which is trained to
respond to nuclear accidents or terrorist act. The drives contain
highly technical nuclear weapons data needed to render weapons safe
in an emergency, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It provides the tools for nuclear physicists and weapons
designers (on the response team) to do their work,'' said Habiger,
who declined to be more specific. He also refused to acknowledge a
report that the drives included information on Russian nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the computer drives are found, it is an embarrassment
for the Los Alamos lab, where the nuclear bomb was built more than
a half-century ago. The lab was the center of a security
controversy during most of 1999 surrounding allegations against one
of its former scientists, Wen Ho Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was arrested in December on a 59-count indictment that
charged him with copying top secret computer files that have never
been found. Although under investigation for three years in
connection with the alleged loss of U.S. nuclear secrets to China,
Lee has not been charged with espionage. In jail awaiting trial,
Lee has denied giving secrets to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours after disclosure of the latest incident, some
members of Congress questioned whether security had improved. It
demonstrates that ''the Department of Energy and its labs still
have a long way to go,'' said Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., the Commerce
Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an extremely serious matter, and we are taking swift
actions to deal with it,'' said John Browne, the Los Alamos lab
director. The drives disappeared from a vault in the highly secured
''X Division'' where the lab's nuclear weapons designers work.
</P>
<P>
   Officials intimately involved in the investigation gave this
account of events:
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos lab officials late on May 7 found the two drives
missing when they checked the vault as wildfires threatened the
laboratory complex. Three days later the lab was evacuated because
of the fire and did not resume operation until May 22, preventing a
detailed search for the material.
</P>
<P>
   After May 22, Los Alamos officials began searching computers,
safes, containers and vaults and interviewed staff members with
access to the vault, but did not report the missing material for 10
days. A week ago, 22 FBI agents and 12 DOE investigators, led by
Habiger, flew to Los Alamos to search and question those with
access to the vault. They have found no trace, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
