<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Students Attend Summer School  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- All year, Wayne Proctor watched his
second-grade daughter struggle with learning fractions and counting
money. So when her teacher recommended summer school for math,
Proctor was grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the long haul, we have to begin to realize that summer
school is not a punishment,'' said Proctor, a copy center manager
whose daughter Jeannelle, 8, attends Stevens Elementary in the
District of Columbia. ''I know she's not a person who hates school.
This year has just been different from what she's used to.''
</P>
<P>
   More students than ever are swamping summer school classes as
educational systems seek to end social promotion of students who
aren't ready for the next grade or provide enrichment programs for
more successful pupils.
</P>
<P>
   District of Columbia schools estimate that 22,000 of its 71,000
students will be back in class when the academic year ends next
week, up slightly from last year. New York City schools expect
250,000 students this summer, seven times what the million-student
district had last year. And Detroit schools, requiring summer
classes for the first time, project 30,000 to 35,000 of their
167,000 total students will attended summer school, a fourfold
increase over the 1999 voluntary program.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a third of the nation's 15,000 districts require summer
school classes for children who fail certain standardized tests,
receive low marks from teachers or skip school regularly. Twice as
many offer special classes, summer camps and fun activities for
younger children and non-working high school students.
</P>
<P>
   As enrollments rise, so do costs. Five weeks of summer schooling
for its mandatory Summer Academies of Learning program will cost
Detroit $12 million for staff, supplies and other needs, which
officials said was about four times the expense of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, it has been a tremendous strain on the budget,'' said
Stan Childress, Detroit schools spokesman, ''but we have to take
the first step to end social promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and other policymakers have urged school
districts to abandon social promotion, a practice allowing students
to move up to the next level even if they have not mastered the
basics for the current grade.
</P>
<P>
   There's been some opposition to banning the practice, usually
from educators who warn that holding students back can be just as
harmful and unproductive if the type and quality of summer
instruction isn't better than what they received during the school
year. But districts have forged ahead with expanding their summer
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, officials looked at transportation, food service and
other support services with an eye toward streamlining the costs or
privatizing the operations altogether, Childress said.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia schools, whose summer school budget
went from $14 million last year to $9 million this year in an
across-the-board school spending cutback, has had to cut out a week
and reduce some training for aides. Mary H. Gill, deputy chief
academic officer for the system, said the programs should be
thought of as essential.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not baby-sitting by any means,'' Gill said. ''Everyone
can't afford to send their children to the best of camps or other
things that are going to enrich their minds. We are trying to make
sure the growth that's made during the year is sustained. It's good
use of our tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Even private and charter schools -- without the outright public
mandates to boost learning -- are increasing summer programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see an opportunity to do some things with the students that
we've not been able to do within the regular school year,'' said
Kenneth Green, principal of the Booker T. Washington Public Charter
School in the district. Roughly 60 of the high school's 149
students will start classes June 26 to catch up on graduation
credits in English and algebra or enrichment courses on photography
or making television documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   Green said the school's administrators and parents readily
agreed to support the programs, knowing the children would be
productive over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't buy into the fact that learning should stop,'' Green
said. ''I've seen what happens over the summer and you start back
in September with a great deal of catching up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 0122 </TRAILER>
