<HEADLINE> Warrant Issued for Mexican Activist  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas (AP) -- Mexican police issued an arrest warrant
Monday for a Mexican activist who promised to pay $10,000 for
anyone who killed a U.S. Border Patrol agent.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant charges Carlos Ibarra Perez, 60, a former oil
worker, of publicly provoking the commission of a crime, The
(McAllen) Monitor reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ibarra, a spokesman for an advocacy group called the Citizen
Defense Committee, said he made the offer because too many
undocumented immigrants were being slain by federal agents and
private landowners while making their way into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Ibarra denied he made the offer during an interview
at a San Diego radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm saying a different thing now,'' Ibarra told KFMB through
an interpreter. ''I'm saying that we avoid violence. I'm saying
we're not supporting this situation of sending people to kill
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities said they issued the warrant after
interviewing about a dozen reporters who attended a June 5 press
conference in Reynosa, Mexico, when Ibarra announced the reward.
</P>
<P>
   ''Provoking a crime, whether it be inside or outside this
country, is a crime and I have the necessary elements to
prosecute,'' said Jesus Trevino, a prosecutor with the Tamaulipas
state attorney general's office in Reynosa.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Ibarra could face up to a year in jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
