<HEADLINE> Wildfire Burns Colo. Homes  </HEADLINE>
By P. SOLOMON BANDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) -- A fast-moving wildfire burned houses
on Monday, forcing residents to flee with only their pets and
prompting the evacuation of nearly 180 girls and staff members from
a Girl Scout camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Hi Meadow Fire burned at least 2,000 acres, destroyed at
least four houses and forced 200 to 300 people to evacuate from
houses near Bailey, about 35 miles southwest of Denver, said Doug
Lee, a spokesman for the fire management team. No injuries were
reported.
</P>
<P>
   A second fire near a subdivision in the mountains west of
Loveland had burned at least two homes, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   They were the most damaging wildfires burning across a number of
Western states, including Arizona, California, New Mexico and Utah.
Smoke from both blazes hung over parts of the Denver metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   The Hi Meadows fire began Monday morning and rapidly spread
through parched brush and timber. The cause was not known, but the
region has had little moisture in months. About 100 firefighters
were on the lines.
</P>
<P>
   David Wortman and his wife loaded their horses into a trailer,
hitched it to their pickup and fled with their dog when the flames
came within 50 yards of their house. They could feel the heat
inside the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once I saw the flames that close, we had to get out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials evacuated 140 girls and 38 staffers from the Flying G
camp as a precaution, even though the fire was moving away from the
camp, said Rachelle Trujillo, a spokeswoman for the Girl Scouts'
Mile High Council.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze near Loveland in Larimer County grew from 40 acres
late in the morning to about 2,000 acres by evening, authorities
said. Two structures had burned and some 300 were threatened but no
injuries had been reported, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross opened shelters near both fires, and Gov. Bill
Owens said the Colorado National Guard was ready to help.
</P>
<P>
   Only three people registered to stay at a Red Cross shelter in
Loveland, but more than 200 registered at two shelters near Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of tension in both the shelters,'' Red Cross
spokesman Matt Bertram said. ''There will be no good night's sleep
here tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
