<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Cabinet Backs Gore  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the Reagan White House, ''Bush for
President'' neckties weren't passed around until late August. But
Cabinet-level electioneering for Al Gore is well underway in the
Clinton White House -- with nary a distinction between the old guard
and the wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   No longer dogmatic about disentangling himself from the Clinton
administration, Gore is stumping this week with former Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, whom campaign insiders have nicknamed ''the
running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's embrace of Gore ''is a very positive and powerful symbol
of continuity in economic policy, given Rubin's track record, is
recognized on Wall Street and Main Street as well,'' said economist
Mark Zandi of RFA Dismal Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest speak-no-ill phase, Gore also is relying on
administration stars to step up to the microphone and criticize
Republican rival George W. Bush's policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Recent examples:
</P>
<P>
   -- Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala gathered
campaign reporters on a conference call to denounce Bush's
long-term care proposal hours after he announced it in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   -- Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo challenged Bush on gun control
in exactly the same language Gore used a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   -- Even Republican Defense Secretary William Cohen joined in,
disguising criticism of Bush's arms control agenda as a polite
offer to brief Bush on defense issues.
</P>
<P>
   -- Army Secretary Louis Caldera accompanied Gore on an official
trip to the West Point commencement ceremony and defended the vice
president's speech -- a veiled criticism of Bush's arms-control
strategy -- as perfectly apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   Some Clinton administration surrogates have made clear they
would relish being part of a Gore administration, most prominently
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who has campaigned with the vice
president and is mentioned as a possible running mate.
</P>
<P>
   This record of assists underscores Gore's intention to soften
his image by leaving the attacks to others, but also the dearth of
heavyweight surrogates he can call his own.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Tipper, daughter, Karenna and Army buddy Bob Delabar
are about the only people campaigning for Gore who are not
acquainted with him by virtue of the fact that he was selected by
Bill Clinton as his running mate in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of policy advisers on Gore's campaign payroll
(there are basically two) is evident when the likes of
Environmental Protection Agency chief Carol Browner, Education
Secretary Richard Riley and National Economic Council chairman Gene
Sperling tag along with Gore to brief reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton-Gore administration is very much like an extended
family. Gore's been an integral part of this administration and has
great relationships with people at virtually every level of this
administration,'' said campaign spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see that as a tremendous asset. The American people clearly
want to continue with the policies of this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, then-Vice President George Bush used Ronald Reagan's
Cabinet in the same way, enlisting them on the day that Housing
Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr. handed out campaign neckties during
a Cabinet meeting and announced, ''Guys, it's now time to get on
board and push for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the younger Bush, Gore's use of surrogates so directly
tied to the president fits the twin arguments that electing Gore
would be like giving Clinton a third term, and that Gore has no
core of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes it's hard to know who Al Gore is and what he really
believes in. To the degree he attaches himself to President Clinton
then detaches himself, it compounds his problem,'' said Bush
campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer. ''There doesn't seem to be a
strong guiding philosophy other than the political
play-of-the-moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush partisans also bristle at the built-in advantage Gore's
well-placed allies give him.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Bush charged the Education Department with spending
taxpayer dollars to campaign against him and Riley said his words
had been manipulated by Bush for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Fleischer suggested that all the political
activity in service to Gore had put government business on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ''With so much more that we can get done this year, like saving
Social Security, reforming Medicare and improving education, the
(Cabinet secretaries') time would be better spent solving the
nation's problems than engaging in attack partisan politics on
behalf of Al Gore,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 0139 </TRAILER>
