<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Searching for new ways to combat resurgence of West Nile like virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - Taking matters into their own hands,
the Dutchess County Legislature on Monday approved spending
$675,000 to kill the larvae of mosquitoes that carry the West Nile
virus.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been no evidence that the virus has ever been
present in Dutchess County, the announcement last week that two
dead birds found in nearby Rockland County were carrying the virus
have heightened fears about West Nile.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, West Nile - first misdiagnosed as St. Louis
encephalitis - killed six people in New York City and one in
Westchester and sickened more than 60. It was also blamed for
hundreds of bird deaths - mostly crows - in New York, New Jersey
and Connecticut, and it killed several horses on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Caldwell, Dutchess County's health commissioner, is
hopeful the $675,000 will allow a larvaciding application program
to begin in early July.
</P>
<P>
   The money should cover at least three rounds of applications in
approximately 50,000 municipal catch basins and other water
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The recent heavy rains would have wiped out any existing
mosquito larvae - which breed mainly in standing water, according
to Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're really right at the right time,'' Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the county spent $171,990 to publicize residents'
role in combating mosquito problems and to contract with Hudsonia
Ltd., a nonprofit research and environmental research group, to
provide surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell said his department is citing people whose property has
unusually large amounts of trash or tires, which contribute to the
development of mosquito larvae.
</P>
<P>
   While most people comply once notified, those who don't could
face consequences. ''Eventually, people could be fined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three New York lawmakers said they will seek to triple the
federal money available to battle the West Nile Virus that left
seven people dead in the New York City area last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, Reps. Nita Lowey, D-Westchester County,
and Joseph Crowley, D-Queens, said they will push for $15 million
over the next two years - $5 million this fiscal year and $10
million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That is up from the $5 million in federal funds that has already
been appropriated.
</P>
<P>
   The money would go to the Centers for Disease Control to fund
research about how the virus spreads and the best ways to eradicate
it.
</P>
<P>
   Costs of combatting the mosquitos that carry the virus have been
left to state and city officials. New York shelled out $10 million
last year to spray the pesticide malathion from helicopters and on
other efforts to kill virus-bearing mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus can cause a range of symptoms. In the most
serious cases, infection can result in encephalitis, or swelling of
the brain. Elderly individuals, or those with compromised immune
systems, are most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Birds harbor the disease and many are susceptible to it, but
they cannot transmit it to humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
