<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bancomer Board Backs Bank Merger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The board of Mexico's second-largest bank has
backed a planned merger with a Spanish banking giant, opening the
door to the most dramatic foray into Mexico by a foreign banking
heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   The board of Bancomer said late Monday that it is recommending
shareholders approve the merger with the local unit of Spanish
banking giant Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria SA.
</P>
<P>
   Bancomer said in a press release that a reworked merger plan
with BBVA's unit Grupo Financiero BBV-Probursa SA calls for a total
capital investment of $2.5 billion, of which $1.4 billion will come
from BBVA.
</P>
<P>
   Under the original terms of the deal, BBVA had agreed to invest
about $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''This alliance is unbeatable,'' BBVA chairman Emilio Ybarra
said in a separate press release. ''It represents a great
opportunity both for Bancomer and for BBVA, and therefore for
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The merged company, to be called Grupo Financiero BBVA-Bancomer,
will be one of Latin America's largest financial institutions. The
new company will have more than $366 million in assets and about
2,000 bank branches throughout Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is expected to take place July 1, though it still
needs shareholder and regulatory approval. Bancomer is planning a
shareholders meeting for June 29.
</P>
<P>
   The planned merger marks the first time a foreign bank has
forged an alliance with a Mexican bank without the federal
government's help. Global heavyweights have been poised to move in
since Mexico eliminated a law in late 1998 that prevented foreign
companies from acquiring more than a 20 percent stake in banks with
more than a 6 percent market share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
