<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Island Premier To Resign  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- The prime minister of the
Solomon Islands said Tuesday that he has no safe choice but to
resign despite worries that the move could cause more rebel
fighting and lead to the breakup of the South Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
   In an exclusive interview with The Associated Press, Bartholomew
Ulufa'alu also said his government could have solved the tensions
flaring over two battling rebel groups if New Zealand and Australia
had sent a few hundred troops to help bring stability to the main
island of Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu said he would stand down Thursday, regardless of the
outcome of a parliamentary vote of no confidence on his leadership
set for that day. He dismissed the vote as an attempt to give a
forced change of leadership a veneer of legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was the result of a deal with rebels who seized
Ulufa'alu at gunpoint June 5 and demanded that he resign. A few
days later, they released him and allowed him to stay in office
until the parliament decided his future.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the entire process ''a sheer mockery of democracy,''
Ulufa'alu said he is resigning under duress, fearing that the
rebels would harm his family and Cabinet ministers if he stayed in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be part of the new government,'' Ulufa'alu
said in his small wood-paneled office in the capital, Honiara. The
vote ''is an insult to my integrity, to my family and the people in
my constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   Chain-smoking and looking despondent with his shirt half
untucked, Ulufa'alu said he comes from a big tribe and his ''people
are not going to just sit back.'' When asked if they might take up
arms and seek revenge, the prime minister said, ''Others can do it.
Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict involves Isatabu residents of Guadalcanal who have
been forcing migrant Malaitans back to Malaita island 60 miles
away. In the past 18 months, about 20,000 Malaitans have been
kicked off Guadalcanal, where the nation's capital is located.
</P>
<P>
   In response, a group called the Malaita Eagle Force raided an
armory a week ago and used the weapons to stage a stunning seizure
of the capital and Ulufa'alu.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the out-armed Isatabus have retreated to the
countryside, while Malaitan rebels have set up checkpoints around
the capital. In the city, the rebels have taken over police duties,
preventing looting and unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu blamed New Zealand and Australia for refusing his
request several weeks ago to send a few hundred troops to help
bring stability to Guadalcanal. The two regional powers have a
responsibility for keeping stability in the South Pacific, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this sprawling group of islands of 455,000 people, made up
of a complex mix of tribes and islanders is on the verge of
splitting, Ulufa'alu said. The Solomon Islands, a former British
colony, became self-governing in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do Australians want this country to be fragmented?'' asked the
prime minister, elected in 1997. ''Would it be cheaper for them to
have three, five or six separate countries? This is something
Australian and New Zealand voters should realize because it's going
to fall sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia is the largest aid donor to the Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, foreign ministers from Australia and New Zealand
were part of a delegation that visited, seeking a peaceful solution
to the crisis. The officials told the government that the two
nations wouldn't consider sending troops until leaders in the
Solomon Islands can negotiate a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Ulufa'alu said such an agreement will be highly unlikely
because the Malaita rebels will not want to return their stolen
machine guns and other weapons -- the sources of their influence on
the next government.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very dangerous precedent we are about to set and the
same thing (a coup) will happen again,'' said Ulufa'alu, an
economist and former consultant to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   There has been concern that most of the 50 members of parliament
will not show up for Thursday's vote, fearing for their safety. But
the vote can take place if lawmakers do not request that the
parliament speaker demand a quorum, or 26 total votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon Islands are a chain of six main islands and dozens
of smaller ones lying 1,600 miles northeast of Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The main island of Guadalcanal was the scene of a bloody and
drawn-out World War II battle, when U.S. Marines began their
island-hopping Pacific assault on Japanese forces after the attack
on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
