<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Gore Behind Bush On Leadership  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Al Gore launches a ''prosperity tour'' to
boast of economic progress, slightly more of the public says in a
poll that it trusts George W. Bush to manage the economy.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC-Washington Post poll released Monday showed that 46
percent of Americans said they trusted Bush, the Republican, with
the economy more than Democrat Gore, 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the vice president, embarks Tuesday on a three-week tour
of key swing states to trumpet the economic expansion that has
taken place during the Clinton-Gore years.
</P>
<P>
   Public reservations about Gore extend to his leadership skills.
By a 2-to-1 margin, respondents said they thought Bush, the Texas
governor, was a strong leader, but were evenly split on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's vulnerabilities don't appear to have created a huge
gulf between him and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Among registered voters, Bush was favored by 49 percent and Gore
by 44 percent, close to the margin between them a month ago in the
same poll. Including Reform Party contender Pat Buchanan and Green
Party candidate Ralph Nader in a four-way race did not alter the
dynamics significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore were ranked about even on the issue of Social
Security, traditionally a strong area for Democrats. Bush's
proposal to let Americans invest part of their Social Security
taxes in the stock market has proven popular, according to other
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was more trusted to understand the problems of average
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Three-fourths of those polled said they consider the American
economy excellent or good. But Gore has been unable to turn that
general optimism to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On tour, Gore will boast about budget surpluses that have
replaced deficits, stock market growth and other signs of a robust
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans scoff that Gore isn't responsible for the nation's
prosperity, but say it was the result of a combination of factors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had an 8-point lead among men, while the two were basically
even among women. Gore needs to match Bush's advantage among men
with a consistent lead among women.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,204 adults was taken Thursday through Sunday and
has an error margin of 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
