<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Hurricane Forecasts Sought  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While researchers are working to improve
hurricane forecasts, many believe that more lives and property can
be saved by being better prepared to face the storms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The impact of the next hurricane is being decided right now --
in the days, weeks and months of preparation that are required to
make communities resistant to disaster,'' James Lee Witt, director
of the Federal Emergency Management Agency, told a conference on
hurricane preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Witt spoke as top hurricane specialists gathered with emergency
management planners and broadcasters to discuss hurricane
forecasting and preparedness. The conference was sponsored by the
American Meteorological Society and The Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mitigation will probably save more lives and property than
improving the forecast,'' agreed Richard Anthes, president of the
University Corp. for Atmospheric Research.
</P>
<P>
   ''But there is room for improving the forecast,'' he added.
''Hurricanes do have inherent predictability.''
</P>
<P>
   UCAR, based in Boulder, Colo., is a consortium of 63 colleges
and universities that do weather and climate research.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane forecasters struggle to predict the path a storm will
take, how fast it will move and, perhaps most difficult, how strong
it will be.
</P>
<P>
   But hurricanes -- also known as tropical cyclones and typhoons --
can do the unexpected, suddenly changing direction, rapidly getting
stronger, or just drifting along the coast, threatening for days
before turning inland.
</P>
<P>
   D. James Baker, head of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, noted that hurricane track forecast error has been
reduced over the last few decades. In the 1960s and 70s,
forecasters could predict 24 hours ahead of time a hurricane's path
within about 100 nautical miles, he said, and now they can predict
it within about 80 nautical miles. And 72 hours ahead of time, the
error has cut in half, from 400 nautical miles to 200 nautical
miles, he said. A nautical mile is 1.15 statute miles.
</P>
<P>
   One forecast that most seem to agree on is that more storms are
likely, for a variety of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes seem to occur more often in some decades and less
often in others, with the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico heading into
a more intense period, experts say. In addition, La Nina cooling of
the Pacific Ocean that remains under way tends to be associated
with years of more Atlantic hurricanes. And many believe that
global warming will result in more and stronger storms.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials stressed the need for more lead
time in forecasts to give them time to evacuate people if needed.
But forecasters noted that increased lead time means warning a
larger area because of the uncertainty of what a storm will do.
</P>
<P>
   Because of rapid growth there are many areas of the coastline
that are so heavily populated that people are going to have to take
action well before the watch-warning phase, said Max Mayfield,
director of the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Witt noted that ''one out of every five people in the United
States is now at direct risk every year. In the 1990's over 2.5
million people relocated to the Southeast.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Elsberry of the Naval Postgraduate School in Monterey,
Calif., urged forecasters to seek a way to include a measure of
confidence in their forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Witt noted that traffic jams that occurred during the massive
evacuation in Hurricane Floyd forced state and federal officials to
review past practices.
</P>
<P>
   ''The good news was that hundreds of thousands of people in
several states responded to evacuation orders,'' Witt observed.
''The bad news was that their response -- which turned into the
largest evacuation in American history -- overwhelmed transportation
infrastructure in four states.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Meteorological Society: http://www.ametsoc.org/AMS
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Channel: http://www.weather.com
</P>
<P>
   Federal Emergency Management Agency: http://www.fema.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration:
http://www.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   University Corporation for Atmospheric Research:
http://www.ucar.edu
</P>
<P>
   Naval Postgraduate School: http://www.nps.navy.mil/
</P>
</TEXT>
