<HEADLINE> Dow Down 62 Early; Nasdaq Drops 48  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mostly lower Tuesday after Wall
Street investment firm Sanford Bernstein cut its rating and
earnings estimates for Hewlett-Packard. The downgrade raised
concerns that technology companies will not meet investors' lofty
expectations for profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 61.52 to 10,502.69.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 1.87 to 1,444.13, and the Nasdaq composite index
was down 47.89 at 3,720.02.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell $7.625 to $118.375, contributing most to
the Dow's decline. Sanford Bernstein lowered its rating on
Hewlett-Packard to a ''market perform'' from ''buy'' and reduced
earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   A broad range of technology companies fell as investors worried
that they, too, will see slower earnings growth. Qualcomm fell
$1.625 to $80.063 and Yahoo! fell $2.188 to $135.25.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in technology kept the broad market from advancing
even after a favorable report on retail sales. The Commerce
Department said retail sales fell for the second month in a row in
May, the latest sign that six interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve are successfully slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took the news as a sign that the Fed might hold rates
steady at its next meeting on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   Still, retail companies that are bearing the brunt of consumers'
moderating behavior fell. Wal-Mart fell $1 to $51.75.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 112.65 million
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.59 to 502.92.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.4 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.6 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
