<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall, Led by Hewlett-Packard  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower Tuesday after Wall
Street investment firm Sanford Bernstein cut its rating and
earnings estimates for Hewlett-Packard. The downgrade raised
concerns that technology companies will not meet investors' lofty
expectations for profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 26.17 to 10,538.04.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 3.98 to 1,449.98, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 31.29 at 3,736.62.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell $7.75 to $118.25, contributing most to the
Dow's decline. Sanford Bernstein lowered its rating on
Hewlett-Packard to a ''market perform'' from ''buy'' and reduced
earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone thinks the disease is going to spread to the entire
sector,'' said Don Selkin, chief investment strategist at Joseph
Gunnar in New York. ''We don't think that's the case. Technology
companies should still outpace the S&AMP;P 500 in terms of earnings
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a broad range of technology companies fell as investors
worried that they, too, will see slower earnings growth. IBM fell
$1.25 to $117.625 and Yahoo! fell $2.188 to $135.25.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in technology kept the broad market from advancing
even after a favorable report on retail sales. The Commerce
Department said retail sales fell for the second month in a row in
May, the latest sign that six interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve are successfully slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, revised figures showed that retail sales fell 0.6
percent in April, much weaker than the government estimated one
month ago. The combination of two weaker-than-expected months at
the nation's stores allowed investors to hope that the Fed might
hold rates steady at its next meeting on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got the number the market wanted, but the market is
overreacting to the negative and disregarding the positive,''
Selkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Retail companies that are bearing the brunt of consumers'
moderating behavior fell. Wal-Mart slipped 18.75 cents to $52.563.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 264.71 million
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.61 to 502.90.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
