<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Soap Operas Focus on Lessons  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The young lovers are quarreling and, in
soap-opera fashion, a meddling mother-in-law is having her say.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more at stake than romance: The teen-age bride wants
to stay in school while her husband is demanding she be a
stay-at-home wife.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thrash her if she raises her voice,'' the mother-in-law
advises with a slap and a snarl. ''Burn her books.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to 200 million viewers in India tuned in weekly to the TV
serial ''Humraahi'' for such juicy drama. What they also got was a
morality play about the importance of respecting women and the
possibility that girls might seek more than an early marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons, not lip gloss, are the hallmark of the television and
radio soaps developed by Population Communications International, a
privately funded, 15-year-old nonprofit organization based in New
York but with a very wide reach.
</P>
<P>
   Working with local partners and officials on four continents, in
countries including China, Kenya, Mexico and Brazil, PCI tackles
such sensitive issues as family planning, gender equality and AIDS
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The homefront isn't ignored: On Saturday, PCI will hold its
second ''Prime Time Summit,'' meeting with TV producers and writers
in Hollywood to encourage them to examine topics including
diversity and domestic violence in their series. Similar meetings
have been held with the soap opera industry since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to use soap operas to change attitudes or to
encourage behaviors that help the public health,'' said PCI
president David J. Andrews. ''To the extent we can capture and
maintain the audience's attention over years of episodes, we can do
a lot to have a direct influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Fox, PCI senior vice president for U.S. programs, said
there can be a ''derisive attitude'' toward soap operas: '''You're
using this silly thing to deal with profound issues.' But soap
operas are internationally popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike dry lectures or books, serials are a sugar-coated
approach. PCI's longest-running show, the 7-year-old radio drama
''Twende na Wakati'' (Let's Go with the Times), is practically an
institution in Tanzania, said Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know of a soap opera in Madagascar that was so popular that
the bishop of a church there had to change the hour of the Mass
because so many people were home watching the show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bai Xing'' (Ordinary People), PCI's Chinese serial that
focused on women's status and the preference for male babies, was
honored by China's Ministry of Culture. After just two weeks on the
air last June, it was also the most-watched serial on Channel 8.
</P>
<P>
   That PCI's programs achieve popularity and government acceptance
seems remarkable given their loaded topics and the possibility they
could be perceived as U.S. dabbling.
</P>
<P>
   The group is aware of the inherent challenge, Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we went to countries with preconceived values or cultural
biases, we would be guilty as charged,'' he said. ''The secret of
our success is we don't do that. ... The countries identify their
own issues, identify their own stories, create their own
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ''What really comes out of it is magical in that the story is so
rooted and so based in the cultural context of that country,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   PCI ventures into a nation only upon invitation and meets with
various officials, including government and religious
representatives, to determine a serial's content.
</P>
<P>
   ''The local teams prioritize themes,'' said Kate Randolph, PCI
vice president for international programs. ''In Kenya, female
circumcision was a theme that came up prominently in research. We
wouldn't say, 'This is a big problem, you have to address it.' They
chose to address it, and in the first year.''
</P>
<P>
   A PCI show has never been pulled off the air, said Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Kimani Njogu, who is head script writer for the Kenyan radio
serial ''Ushikwapo Shikamana'' (If Assisted, Assist Yourself) and
has worked on PCI series in other countries, said sensitivity is
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ''We respect cultures, even as we seek to intervene,'' Njogu
said. ''Moreover, we always seek to provide all possible arguments
for and against the issue at hand so that religious, cultural,
gender arguments are heard on air.''
</P>
<P>
   PCI soaps feature strongly ''negative'' characters -- such as a
drug-dealing, philandering husband who exposes his wife to the risk
of HIV infection -- and upright role models.
</P>
<P>
   ''The positive characters are usually rewarded. Not with cars or
jewelry, but with lives that get better,'' Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   The format can be effective, according to a University of New
Mexico study released last year. In Tanzania, where the average
woman has more than five children, those who listened to ''Twende
na Wakati'' were twice as likely to adopt family planning.
</P>
<P>
   PCI, which counts among its financial supporters the Ford
Foundation and Bill Gates, also is conducting a year-long public
awareness campaign that asks Americans to consider their role in
population growth. With Walter Cronkite as honorary chairman, the
campaign began last fall when the planet reached 6 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   PCI's focus, initially limited to population control through
family planning, broadened in 1994 after a 179-nation conference in
Egypt on population and development.
</P>
<P>
   ''The realization hit home that what really makes a difference
is when population is addressed in the context of women's rights,''
Andrews said, adding that ''soap operas seem able to absorb an
enormous number of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL RIGHTS: Justice may yet prevail for victims of decades-old
civil-rights attrocities. Last week, 34 years after the racially
charged murder of a Mississippi black man, Ben Chester White, the
U.S. Justice Department announced the indictment of Ernest Avants,
who has lived freely since his acquittal on state murder charges in
1966. A ''20/20'' report by correspondent Connie Chung last
November uncovered information that led federal investigators to
re-open the case after more than three decades. Chung updates the
story tonight (June 14) at 10 p.m. Eastern on ABC News' ''20/20.''
Her hour-long report also unveils the identity of an FBI informant
and former Ku Klux Klansman who, for the first time, provides
information about who murdered two Mississippi black men, Charles
Moore and Henry Dee, in 1964. ''I'd like to clear my conscience,''
the man tells Chung.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1153 </TRAILER>
