<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Drops 23, Dow Down 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Tuesday after Wall Street
investment firm Sanford Bernstein cut its rating and earnings
estimates for Hewlett-Packard. The downgrade raised concerns that
technology companies will not meet investors' lofty expectations
for profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the broad market was holding up relatively well after a
muted retail sales report raised hopes that the Federal Reserve
will soon stop raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 2.13 at 10,562.08. The blue-chip index had pared
an early loss of as much as 71 points.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 9.06 at 1,455.06, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 23.18 at 3,744.73.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell $7.813 to $118.188, pulling the Dow lower.
Sanford Bernstein lowered its rating on Hewlett-Packard to a
''market perform'' from ''buy'' and reduced earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone thinks the disease is going to spread to the entire
sector,'' said Don Selkin, chief investment strategist at Joseph
Gunnar in New York. ''We don't think that's the case. Technology
companies should still outpace the S&AMP;P 500 in terms of earnings
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a broad range of technology companies fell as investors
worried that they, too, will see slower earnings growth. IBM fell
$1.25 to $117.625 and Yahoo! fell $2.75 to $134.688.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in technology kept the broad market from advancing
even after a favorable report on retail sales. The Commerce
Department said retail sales fell for the second month in a row in
May, the latest sign that six interest rate increases by the Fed
are successfully slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, revised figures showed that retail sales fell 0.6
percent in April, much weaker than the government estimated one
month ago. The combination of two weaker-than-expected months at
the nation's stores allowed investors to hope that the Fed might
hold rates steady at its next meeting on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got the number the market wanted, but the market is
overreacting to the negative and disregarding the positive,''
Selkin said.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, scattered gains were helping pull the Dow toward
positive territory. Merck rose $2.938 to $72.875 and AT&AMP;T rose
$1.125 to $34.625.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 391.40 million
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.08 to 504.43.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
