<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Department May Be Audited  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers angered over fraud in the
Education Department -- including a $1 million employee theft ring --
approved legislation requiring the agency be audited by
congressional investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 380-19 Tuesday to direct the General Accounting
Office, Congress' auditing arm, to study department accounts
particularly prone to abuse. Last month, federal officials
discovered an employee theft ring that had cost the agency more
than $1 million in stolen equipment and falsely reported overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The department, whose budget is more than $32 billion and which
manages billions more in student loans, also has paid grant winners
twice and forgiven loans for fraudulent borrowers. Rep. Pete
Hoekstra, main sponsor of the legislation, said the agency sent
duplicate checks to contractors and grantees this year totaling
about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are talking about some of the most important dollars that
we spend in Washington today,'' said Hoekstra, R-Mich., chairman of
the House Education and Workforce oversight subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said a special probe is unwarranted because
its internal auditors have worked with the FBI and other
investigators to uncover fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is our position that the inspector general, whenever there
is any question raised of wrongdoing or fraud, has thoroughly and
promptly investigated,'' said Erica Lepping, spokeswoman for
Education Secretary Richard Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Independent auditors the department hired to review fiscal year
1998 financial records concluded they could not offer an opinion on
the agency's accounting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are dealing with this issue because of the Department of
Education's inability to receive a clean audit,'' said Hoekstra.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the department's internal watchdog nor the independent
auditing firm has confirmed any financial mismanagement. Education
Department Inspector General Lorraine Lewis would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill was opposed only by Democrats. Sen. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., is pushing a similar bill in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Jarmon, who handles education and other issues for the
GAO, said the investigative agency would not duplicate Lewis' work.
The fraud audit, likely to focus on student loans, will examine all
transactions instead of a sample and check documents for forgeries,
rather than ''just accepting documentation at face value.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarmon said the office gets regular requests to examine
agencies, but legislation requiring an audit is not so common.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4079.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.house.gov/hoekstra
</P>
<P>
   Education Department budget page:
http://www.ed.gov/offices/OUS/budget.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1416 </TRAILER>
