<HEADLINE> IMF Chief To Visit African Nations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Horst Koehler, the International Monetary
Fund's managing director, will visit five African nations next
month, the IMF said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler goes to Nigeria on July 2-3, Senegal July 4, Cameroon
July 5, Mozambique July 6, and South Africa July 7-8, the IMF said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The trip's purpose is to ''hear perspectives on critical issues
the African continent is facing,'' the IMF said. ''He is
particularly interested in the views of African countries on the
role of the IMF and its involvement in restructuring their
economies.''
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, who took over as the IMF chief May 2, has already
visited in Latin America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Africa represents a sensitive region politically for the IMF,
given past criticisms that it has contributed to the hardships of
the poorest there by imposing fiscal austerity on nations who
qualify for long-term IMF loans.
</P>
<P>
   Nongovernmental organizations recently criticized the IMF for
its demands that Mozambique sharply cut the sugar tariffs that
protect its struggling sugar industry from import competition.
</P>
<P>
   Many argue that exposing Mozambique's sugar industry to
potential damaging competition will only encourage other African
nations to continue relying on traditional industries, particularly
gold, platinum and diamond mining, that have often been catalysts
for civil wars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1425 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
