<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Warns Burundian Lawmakers  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHE NKURUNZIZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- Nelson Mandela warned Burundian
lawmakers Tuesday that delay in integrating the country's armed
forces would encourage Hutu rebels and prolong the 7-year-old civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you agree to integration, then you occupy higher moral
ground than the rebels. By delaying...you give them space to
continue fighting and killing people,'' the former South African
president told Burundi's National Assembly in the capital,
Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with Mandela last week in South Africa,
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya agreed to incorporate Hutus into
the Tutsi-dominated army.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya needs the support of both the military and top Tutsi
legislators to implement the measure, seen as key to ending a war
that has left at least 200,000 Burundians dead since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to an audience that included military officials,
Cabinet ministers and foreign diplomats, Mandela said he had never
seen a worse jail than Burundi's Mpimba Prison, where he visited
political prisoners on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, who was incarcerated for 27 years in South Africa on
treason charges, invited Burundian officials and diplomats to
inspect Mpimba.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will help me a great deal if you just go and see how human
beings are treated in this country,'' he said. ''I will not recover
(from the shock) until I see the leadership here has taken
responsibility on their shoulders to relieve those people from such
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed release of political prisoners is said to be
holding up peace talks in Tanzania. Mandela said Monday their
release was a prerequisite for peace.
</P>
<P>
   The 81-year-old Mandela took over mediation of the Burundi talks
in December, succeeding the late Tanzanian President Julius
Nyerere. Since then, he has pressed for a resolution, traveling
twice to Arusha and recruiting African and European leaders, as
well as President Clinton, for help in ending the war.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mandela praised Buyoya, a Tutsi, as being ''far
ahead of the leadership in Arusha and the leadership in Bujumbura
in bringing peace in Burundi.''
</P>
<P>
   Burundi's armed forces, as well as its economy and government,
are dominated by minority Tutsis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
