<HEADLINE> Dow Up 63; Nasdaq Rises 44  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly higher Tuesday as investors
seized on the latest retail sales report as evidence that the
economy is slowing just enough to convince the Federal Reserve to
leave interest rates unchanged at its next meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' optimism over the state of the economy helped the
market break out of a slump that started after Wall Street
investment firm Sanford Bernstein cut its rating and earnings
estimates for Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 62.93 at 10,627.14. The blue-chip
index had pared an early loss of as much as 71 points.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 19.94 at 1,465.94, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 43.67 at 3,811.58.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose once investors began focusing on a favorable report
on retail sales. The Commerce Department said retail sales fell for
the second month in a row in May, the latest sign that six interest
rate increases by the Fed are successfully slowing consumer
spending.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, revised figures showed that retail sales fell 0.6
percent in April, much weaker than the government estimated one
month ago. The combination of two weaker than expected months at
the nation's stores allowed investors to hope that the Fed might
hold rates steady at its next meeting on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Fed is finished for the year,'' said Don Selkin, chief
investment strategist at Joseph Gunnar in New York. Selkin pointed
out that May economic figures don't reflect the Fed's last rate
increase, a half-percentage point boost on May 16 that drove rates
to the highest level since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will see more evidence of a slowdown, and with that
evidence in hand, the Fed really won't be able to justify raising
rates any higher,'' Selkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said investors are also concerned that the
highly coveted slowdown, which the Fed hopes will prevent inflation
from rearing up, will eventually hurt corporate earnings. Tuesday,
investors who were ready to buy embraced so-called ''defensive''
stocks -- those whose profits aren't significantly affected by
fluctuations in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Merck rose $3 to $72.938 and Warner Lambert rose $3.688 to
$126.75.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell $7.813 to $118.313, pulling the Dow lower.
Sanford Bernstein lowered its rating on Hewlett-Packard to a
''market perform'' from ''buy'' and reduced earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The warning on Hewlett-Packard prevented most technology stocks
from making significant gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone thinks the disease is going to spread to the entire
sector,'' Selkin said. ''We don't think that's the case. Technology
companies should still outpace the S&AMP;P 500 in terms of earnings
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 717.06 million
shares, well ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.32 to 508.83.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
