<HEADLINE> 'Ulysses' Manuscript Displayed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The original manuscript of James Joyce's
''Ulysses'' went on display Monday for the first time in Dublin,
the city that inspired the modernist masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce's novel records the city in precise detail, as it traces
the wanderings of protagonists Stephen Dedalus and Leopold Bloom on
a day in June, 1904.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce once said that, if Dublin was ever destroyed, it could be
rebuilt using the novel as a blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   But not a world of the book was written in the Irish capital.
Joyce left Dublin in 1904, and wrote ''Ulysses'' between 1914 and
1921 while in Italy, Switzerland and France.
</P>
<P>
   The manuscript is the centerpiece of a Joyce exhibition at
Dublin Castle's Chester Beatty library. The exhibit, which runs
through September, opened just two days before Bloomsday, when
Joyce lovers enact scenes from ''Ulysses'' in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   An impoverished Joyce sold the original manuscript to New York
lawyer and art patron John Quinn for $12,000 dollars before its
1921 publication.
</P>
<P>
   The manuscript was later sold to Philadelphia book dealer and
collector Abraham Rosenbach, and had remained in the United States
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Derick Dreher, director of the Rosenbach Library in
Philadelphia, where the manuscript has been kept since 1924, said
the Dublin exhibition marked the homecoming of a ''quintessentially
Irish'' work.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are amazed that it has never been here before,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
