<HEADLINE> Norwegian Oil Rig Evacuated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Rescue helicopters evacuated most of the 77
crew aboard a Norwegian offshore oil rig after several of its
anchors broke loose in the North Sea, prompting fear that it might
go adrift in a fierce storm.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 nonessential crew members had been evacuated by
helicopter, while 26 were remaining on board to control the rig
with its remaining anchors and engines, said Anders Bang-Andersen,
spokesman for the rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is under control, but storm winds and big waves
are not exactly a dream situation,'' he said. He said no one was
injured or in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Bang-Andersen said the rig had drifted about 925 feet out of
position before the remaining anchor chains took up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   The drilling rig had been working at the Snorre field, about 90
miles northwest of the city of Bergen, on Norway's west coast, when
its anchors dragged, probably due to extreme winds.
</P>
<P>
   According to rescuers, conditions were difficult with winds of
up to 75 mph and waves of up to 40 feet. Meteorologists predicted
that the winds would ease during the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Bang-Andersen said there was no danger of an oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a floating rig, not a permanent installation. It is
the kind of rig that is moved from place to place ... and I have no
information to indicate that it is an any danger of capsizing,''
said Helge Stiksrud, a spokesman for Norsk Hydro, which was
operating the rig.
</P>
<P>
   The Bideford Dolphin is among the most modern drilling rigs
operating off the Norwegian coast and has fully automated operating
systems, according to its owner, the Dolphin ASA concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
