<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad Was a Hero and a Dictator  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA BRYSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- To much of the outside world, the late
Syrian President Hafez Assad was a brutal dictator in the style of
another era, cutting himself and his nation off from the current of
history.
</P>
<P>
   But to many Syrians and to some in neighboring Arab states,
Assad, who died Saturday and was buried Tuesday, was a hero --
simply because he was seen as a man who would stand up to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with a visiting foreign official several years ago,
Assad was pressed to back off some of his territorial claims in
order to strike a peace deal with Israel. He rejected the argument
he could persuade his people to accept concessions, saying, a
witness recalled, that even the palace servants would revolt if he
gave up the land -- and they would be right.
</P>
<P>
   To the end, Assad refused to bend in his negotiations with
Israel over the Golan Heights, the strategic plateau lost in the
1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated United States saw talks it was mediating between
Syria and Israel falter in January. Syria wanted assurances that
Israel would withdraw from the Golan Heights and turn over land
extending down to the Sea of Galilee. Israel refused to make such a
pledge and insisted the issues of security arrangements and
normalization be spelled out first.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had our differences, but I always respected him,''
President Clinton said after learning of Assad's death. Clinton
telephoned Assad's son and heir apparent Bashar to offer
condolences and sent U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
represent the United States at the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was frustrated at failing to get Assad to
strike a peace deal with Israel -- Assad would not even sit down
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. And the envoy he did send,
his foreign minister, refused to shake Barak's hand, a snub that
drew cheers in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The United States considered Syria a sponsor of terrorism.
Groups like New York-based Human Rights Watch decried ''Syria's
bleak human rights record'' because any challenge to government
power was brutally put down.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians who objected ended up in jail or in exile. Others
learned to cope, perhaps clinging all the more fiercely to the idea
of Assad as hero, as if the hardships were a necessary price of
living under an unwavering leader.
</P>
<P>
   Assad dreamed of an Arab world united against Israel. Instead,
Egypt and then Jordan signed peace treaties with the Jewish state,
and the Palestinians opened talks with Israel. Assad finally
decided to pursue negotiations too, when it appeared he and his
proxy state Lebanon would be the only ones left out -- and long
after his preoccupation with foreign affairs had left his
socialist-style economy in a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, though, is still trying to progress from no-war to real
peace with neighbors Egypt, with which it signed a treaty in 1979,
and Jordan, with which it signed a treaty in 1994. Ordinary
Egyptians and Jordanians who resist trade and cultural ties with
their old enemy have looked to Assad as a beacon, and militant
Palestinians who oppose their own leadership's talks with Israel
have found havens in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Dignitaries from at least three dozen countries came to Assad's
funeral. Absent was Israel, still technically at war with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The funerals last year of Jordan's King Hussein and Morocco's
King Hassan II were watersheds, with Israel and many of the nations
at odds with it coming together in grief. Assad attended Hussein's
funeral, the only time he attended an event where Israeli leaders
were present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
