<HEADLINE> Assad's Brother in Southern Spain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARBELLA, Spain (AP) -- Rifaat Assad, the exiled brother of
Syria's late President Hafez Assad, appeared in public Tuesday in
this posh resort town in southern Spain and said he was in deep
mourning.
</P>
<P>
   As his brother was buried in Syria, Assad spoke briefly to
reporters as he went into a whitewashed six-story office and
apartment building in Marbella, accompanied by a handful of
bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in deep sorrow and I hope you appreciate that. I hope
you appreciate our feelings now,'' said Assad, 63, who appeared
tired. ''I hope we get a chance to recuperate from our sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for him, Al-Hareth Al-Khair, told The Associated
Press that Assad stands by a statement he issued Monday opposing
the chosen successor of the late Syrian leader, Hafez Assad's
34-year-old son Bashar Assad, saying he has no right to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ''What (Rifaat Assad) wants is legitimacy to be present'' in
Syria, the spokesman said. ''Bashar is not legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rifaat Assad, who once commanded an elite army unit, has lived
mainly in exile since 1984 after leading an apparent coup attempt
in Damascus while his brother was hospitalized from a heart attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
