<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golan Heights' Druse Mourn Assad  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAJDAL SHAMS, Golan Heights (AP) -- Druse Arabs on the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights closed businesses and hung black
flags of mourning Tuesday for the funeral of Syrian President Hafez
Assad, whom they saw as their leader.
</P>
<P>
   Most Golan Druse consider themselves Syrian in almost every way
-- but living under Israeli rule -- some dared to criticize Assad and
to express doubt about life under Syrian rule.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of separation from Syria, where most of the 17,000
Golan Druse have relatives they haven't seen since Israel captured
the Golan Heights in 1967, was evident as residents of this
bustling town watched Assad's funeral on TV and copied the mourning
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Druse draped black mourning flags, Syrian flags, and pictures of
a young healthy Assad from stores and balconies throughout their
villages, a bold step in a region where Syrian flags attract the
attention of Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   In the main square here, a monument to a Druse hero was covered
with wreaths and pictures of Assad and banners proclaiming ''Your
memory is in our heart always.''
</P>
<P>
   A loudspeaker blared Koranic verses, and private businesses were
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Assad wasn't just any person,'' said Abeer, a gym teacher, 24,
who declined to give her last name because she said that praising
Assad would jeopardize her job as an Israeli public servant.
</P>
<P>
   She bristled at the Israeli education ministry officials who
forced her and other teachers to show up for work even though all
students were honoring a three-day strike in Assad's memory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to feel like a person, that I have a country and a
president,'' she said in halting Hebrew, pointing to the televised
funeral procession. Her brother took a framed picture of Assad from
the closet and hung it on the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in Majdal Shams, Abeer studied in Damascus, where
Golan Druse get free tuition and a stipend for expenses, a gesture
from Assad that signified his claim to the Golan and its residents.
</P>
<P>
   Most Golan Druse refuse Israeli citizenship and pledge their
loyalty to Syria in demonstrations and public statements. They
describe their feelings over Assad's death with phrases similar to
those of mourners in Syria: ''I lost a father,'' ''I lost a piece
of my own flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds held angry demonstrations Monday and Tuesday when
Israel denied most of them permission to cross into Syria for the
funeral. Syria also denied some Druse permission to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Some Druse residents, accustomed to the relatively free speech
allowed under Israel, criticized Assad and the dictatorship he
established.
</P>
<P>
   ''Syria can't continue the way it is now,'' said Yosef Safadi, a
dentist, 36, who said fear of retaliation if Syria regains the
Golan prevented other villagers from speaking against Assad or his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of the most primitive countries in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Safadi is no sympathizer with Israel -- he respects Assad for
demanding that every inch of the Golan be returned to Syria, and he
hopes it happens soon.
</P>
<P>
   He fears however, that Assad's successor -- apparently his son
Bashar -- will continue his father's hard line, cracking down on
personal freedoms and maintaining the isolation that has stifled
Syria's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Safadi also dared to voice doubt that the 34-year-old heir could
hold onto power.
</P>
<P>
   Golan Druse find themselves caught between Israel, resented as a
foreign occupier, and a return to Syria that would likely end the
relative prosperity and freedom that 33 years of Israeli rule have
brought.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small percentage of Golan Druse hold Israeli citizenship
and an even smaller number collaborate with Israeli security
services.
</P>
<P>
   A minority both in Israel and Syria, members of the secretive
Druse religion that is an offshoot of Islam hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bashar will definitely be more open than his father,'' Safadi
said. ''Because it's impossible to be more closed than his
father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
