<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Tycoon Arrested in Russia  </HEADLINE>
By JIM HEINTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Media tycoon Vladimir Gusinsky, whose holdings
include a TV station and newspapers that regularly criticize the
Kremlin over the Chechen war, civil rights and other issues, was
arrested Tuesday on charges of swindling and theft.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a feud with President Vladimir Putin's administration
in recent months, Gusinsky has alleged the Kremlin is persecuting
him because it wants to crack down on independent news media. His
Media-Most holding company is one of Russia's largest media groups
and is widely considered the most outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was taken into custody a month after investigators
backed by masked, gun-toting police raided Media-Most's offices. A
court later ruled the raid, which received widespread attention in
the West, was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest caught the quick attention of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are quite concerned about some of the steps taken against
the free media,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's lawyer, Pavel Astakhov, said the tycoon was called to
the prosecutor-general's office Tuesday for questioning related to
the raid and then arrested, the Interfax news agency reported. He
was being held in a Moscow prison, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   He is alleged to have participated in taking state property
worth at least $10 million, Russian news agencies said, citing a
statement by the prosecutor-general's office.
</P>
<P>
   It said Gusinsky's actions were done in concert with several
unidentified top officials of the Russian state television company
''Russian Video,'' based in St. Petersburg. NTV televison, one of
Gusinsky's companies, reported that ''Russian Video'' head Dmitry
Rozhdestventsky was charged with misappropriation of state funds in
1998 and has been in prison pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, on a state visit to Spain, said he had not known of the
arrest in advance and ''I hope the prosecutor's office has
sufficient grounds and everything was done in keeping with the
law,'' Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
   But Kirill Dibsky, deputy chief editor at the daily newspaper
Segodnya owned by Gusinsky's company, said ''It's an exclusively
political case.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said the raid last month was part of an
investigation into alleged violations of privacy law by the
company's security service. They claimed investigators found
evidence of eavesdropping on politicians, businessmen and
journalists, including bugging devices.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky has long experience in the rough-and-tumble world of
Russian business and politics, starting in the late 1980s when
economic reforms opened the way for entrepreneurs -- and for
questionable deals. Gusinsky emerged as one of the so-called
''Oligarchs'' -- a few men who amassed financial empires overnight
amid widespread allegations of the rigged privatization of state
property.
</P>
<P>
   He established the Most commercial bank in 1989, which snapped
up deteriorating buildings, renovated them and sold them at great
profit. In 1994, Russian media reported his staff was being
investigated on corruption allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gusinsky alleged that Putin's chief of staff
Alexander Voloshin had offered him $100 million for his media not
to impede Putin in the presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, elected president in March, has said he would work to
root out the corruption that has been endemic in Russia since the
collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But Boris Nemtsov, a leading reformist politician, said Tuesday
that the arrest sends a warning to all news media.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't behave you'll also end up in the slammer,'' he
said on ''Glas Naroda,'' (Voice of the People), a discussion show
on NTV television that aired two hours after the arrest was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most's holdings include Segodnya, the radio station Ekho
Moskvy and the NTV television channel. NTV's satirical puppet show,
''Kukly,'' savages Putin and other top officials every week,
reportedly enraging some of the officials who are lampooned.
</P>
<P>
   The company's media are regarded as generally reliable, but in
Russia's highly charged media atmosphere, most publications and
broadcast outlets reflect the political stances of their owners.
</P>
<P>
   Another powerful media figure, Boris Berezovsky, commented
Tuesday on the arrest: ''There is no doubt that any person who did
business in Russia over the last 10 years broke the law, directly
or indirectly'' because the laws are confusing and frequently
changed, Interfax reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
