<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prescription Drug Imports Sought  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sponsors of legislation to allow imports of
federally approved drugs defended the proposal Tuesday against
critics who said such a move would jeopardize safety.
</P>
<P>
   Several bills have been introduced that would lift the U.S. ban
on pharmacists importing drugs from other countries, such as
Canada, where they are cheaper because of government price
controls.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can import lettuce into this country, produced in
hundreds if not thousands of farms, certainly we can make sure that
the quality of (imported drugs) is of the standard that we want it
to be,'' Rep. Bernard Sanders, I-Vt., told the Senate Health,
Education, Labor and Pensions Committee.
</P>
<P>
   His comparison drew a challenge from the Senate's only
physician, committee member Bill Frist, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lettuce importation into this country is different'' than a
drug used to treat a life-threatening illness, Frist said. ''If we
use the same standards that we use for importing lettuce into this
country, then I think we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said his point was that if regulators could certify the
safety of food, they should be able to do the same for prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say allowing imported drugs opens the door to safety
problems such as counterfeiting and tampering. Drugs also could
lose their effectiveness because of long delays in shipping.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota Sen. Byron Dorgan, a Democrat who has sponsored
legislation similar to Sanders', said he would make any changes the
committee feels necessary to ensure safety. But he also noted the
safety argument comes mainly from a pharmaceutical industry
interested in keeping U.S. prices high.
</P>
<P>
   Dorgan, using pill bottles as a prop, said some medicines are
twice as expensive in the United States, forcing some poor
Americans to choose between food and health.
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is to force the re-pricing of drugs in this country,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Dorgan and others who support importation actually
want the federal government to create price controls.
</P>
<P>
   Alan F. Holmer, head of the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America, the drug companies' trade group, noted
Food and Drug Administration Commissioner Jane Henney told Congress
earlier this year that she had safety concerns about imported
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   And he said any move toward government price controls would
chill the industry's innovative research and development efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., who also has sponsored
drug import legislation, questioned why Americans must ''bear all
of the burden of the research and development that benefits the
whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Some committee members said they understood the reasons for the
legislation but wondered if it was the right solution.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn., said the best way to address the
problem is through increased insurance coverage of prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The drug industry is obviously an easy target,'' he said. ''I
don't want to see a solution that's more harmful than the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords' bill is S. 2520
</P>
<P>
   Dorgan's bill is S. 1191
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' bill is H.R. 1885
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1646 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Rejects Execution Moratorium  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The American Medical Association on Tuesday
rejected a proposal for a moratorium on executions, instead calling
for ''appropriate medical forensic techniques'' to be used in
capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Weisbuch, author of the original resolution, had
asked the AMA to recommend to the National Governors' Association
that executions be halted until questions are answered regarding
the availability of DNA evidence and the quality of legal
representation for defendants facing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is one of our tenets to do no harm,'' Weisbuch, public
health director for Maricopa County, Ariz., told the AMA's
550-member House of Delegates on Tuesday. He said that if doctors
do not work with the justice system to ensure capital cases do not
lead to wrongful convictions, ''we are not doing the work that we
should be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA's delegates voted in favor of an amended resolution to
simply ''support the availability and use of all appropriate
medical forensic techniques in the criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates at the AMA's annual meeting also endorsed a
procedure called ''surgical placebo controls,'' in which
participants in trials of a potential therapy might get incisions
or even holes drilled in their head even though only some would get
the actual treatment.
</P>
<P>
   It's a variation on traditional ''placebo controls'' studies, in
which one group of subjects gets a medication and results are
compared with members of a control group who receive a ''placebo''
or dummy pill.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a recent University of Colorado study of the
effectiveness of transplanting fetal pig brain cells into the
brains of Parkinson's disease patients, holes were drilled in the
skulls of 40 patients but only half got the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The government has encouraged such research, but some ethicists
say the practice exposes human placebos to undue risks with no
benefits. The report adopted Tuesday acknowledges the risks but
says surgical placebo studies are justified if risks are made clear
to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty was characterized as a legal issue rather than
a medical one by several physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Calling for a moratorium ''presumes that there isn't a single
state in the nation that's doing the right thing,'' said Dr. Thomas
Price of Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   He said, for example, that ''Texas has done the right thing'' by
recently postponing the execution of an inmate who may be
exonerated by DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Thorson of Fort Collins, Colo., also told the
delegates that he feared a temporary halt would lead to a permanent
moratorium -- something he said wasn't the AMA's business.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion comes in the midst of a national debate over the
death penalty, heightened by Illinois Gov. George Ryan's moratorium
earlier this year after medical evidence exonerated several death
row inmates. The sponsors of the original resolution also noted a
recent Chicago Tribune report that questioned the reliability of
evidence in dozens of Texas executions during Gov. George W. Bush's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The original resolution, drafted by the American Association of
Public Health Physicians, said ''the possibility exists that in
several states innocent individuals may be executed because medical
technology will not be made available in time to prevent their
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Its author, Weisbuch, said he considered Tuesday's vote a
partial victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased with the fact that the AMA recognized ... that
there are people in this country that are being denied adequate
services in a capital punishment environment,'' he said. ''I was
disappointed personally that the association was unwilling to take
the next step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1647 </TRAILER>
