<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Orphans Seek Refuge in US  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAKUMA, Kenya (AP) -- Sitting under a tree to escape the searing
midday heat, Barnabas Yel Atem contemplates what life might be like
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old, who has crisscrossed East Africa on foot,
searching for a haven from war, is one of thousands of young
Sudanese men -- dubbed the ''Lost Boys'' by aid agencies -- who have
grown up as refugees, orphaned or separated from their families.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, Barnabas and 3,500 other Sudanese hope
to be in the United States as part of a resettlement program
established by the U.S. State Department and U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after so many years on the run, Barnabas is skeptical.
''If we reach there, we will forget all these problems ... ,'' he
said, his voice trailing off, tinged with doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Barnabas was among thousands of boys, some as young as
4 or 5, who fled Sudan's 17-year civil war, covering thousands of
miles on foot. Those who made it to neighboring Ethiopia thought
they had found stability. But in 1991, civil war broke out there,
too.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to Sudan, again on foot, but fighting forced them
south toward Kenya, where they ended up at Kakuma, 70 miles south
of the Sudanese border.
</P>
<P>
   ''The journeys were very bad,'' said Barnabas, whose father was
killed in fighting before he left for Ethiopia and whose mother had
died earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no shoes and was thirsty and hungry, and we had to dodge
fighting -- many people died,'' he said. ''Moving from place to
place with such problems, we felt we could not exist in this
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting between southern-based rebels and government forces,
which began again in earnest in 1983, has left at least 2 million
Sudanese dead, mainly from war-induced famine, and forced 4 million
others from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of children who left Sudan for Ethiopia is not
known. But Julianne Duncan, a consultant with the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, said there could have been as many as
30,000.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the boys reached Kakuma, the number had dwindled to
12,000. According to Duncan, many were killed either in fighting,
or by wild animals, hunger or disease. Still others drowned while
crossing rivers.
</P>
<P>
   How the boys began the trek with little adult supervision or why
they congregated in Ethiopia remains a mystery. The boys say
everybody just scattered when their villages were attacked, and
there are stories of teachers or elder boys guiding them.
</P>
<P>
   But they stuck together, spending eight years at the U.N. camp
at Kakuma.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said 5,000 of the original group of boys remain. While
some have gone back to Sudan, for the rest, returning is either too
dangerous or there is nothing to go back to.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after years of deciding what should be done with them, the
U.S. State Department and UNHCR have agreed to resettle about 3,500
young men over 18 in the United States, with the first group
scheduled to arrive by the end of the year, according to Preeta
Law, the UNHCR regional resettlement officer in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   They are to be resettled in regions where significant Sudanese
communities already exist, such as in Texas, Minnesota and North
and South Dakota. Church groups and other volunteer agencies,
working with U.S. government agencies, will help them with grants
and some social services to get started on their new life,
officials in Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   But after so many fruitless journeys, young refugees like
Barnabas still have to be persuaded that a brighter future beckons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have heard about the resettlement program, but it was such a
long time ago I am discouraged,'' he said. ''I don't think it will
happen any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the United Nations seeks to resettle or repatriate
children within two years. However, Law acknowledged it has taken
far longer with the Lost Boys, partly because they were minors when
the process began and were unaccompanied by adults.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan blames the U.N. system, saying the organization too often
focused on emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the conflict in Sudan, the world is not able to
solve this problem and the nature of U.N. bureaucracy has caused
this group of people to be raised in a refugee camp,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kakuma, a dusty sprawling mass of mud huts which now holds
some 90,000 refugees from nine countries in the region, there is
little the Lost Boys can do except play checkers in the shade and
wait.
</P>
<P>
   ''The life here just depends on whatever I feel,'' said
21-year-old William Dhuor. ''Everyone has their own way of
thinking. Some think too much about living here or how to get their
parents. If something is not possible, I cannot put more effort
into that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
