<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Hopes for Better Syria Ties  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The split screen was nothing out of the
ordinary: news anchor in the studio, onsite commentator describing
unfolding events.
</P>
<P>
   It was the captions that told the story: Jerusalem and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   A small delegation of Israeli Arabs attended the funeral Tuesday
of Israel's longtime foe, Syrian President Hafez Assad. Israeli
officials hailed their presence -- and their unprecedented live
broadcasts to Israel -- as signals that Assad's son planned to
revive the collapsed peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although it is not a revolution, it is just one step toward
some kind of more normal relations between neighbors,'' Justice
Minister Yossi Beilin told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, officially in a state of war with Syria, was not invited
to send an official delegation. Most of the 14 Israeli Arabs in the
delegation had visited Syria before; but this was the first time
they crossed directly over the border between the Israeli-occupied
Golan Heights and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the first time they delivered live, high profile
reports to an Israeli broadcaster, the state-run Israel television.
Until now, Syria has banned any contact with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Damascus, which you can see behind me, is a beautiful city, a
noble city, a very historic city,'' legislator Mohammed Barakeh
told Israelis, sweeping his arm toward the panoramic backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   He and other interviewees spoke Hebrew -- a language that not
long ago was banned in Syria, even to Syrian Jews wanting to pray
in Judaism's liturgical tongue.
</P>
<P>
   In what was billed as a ''historic first live feed,'' legislator
Ahmed Tibi said the group was received warmly, and commented that
their easy passage into the country was a positive sign of
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is a sign of a Syrian society opening in the
direction of modernization and openness in all matters,'' he said.
''There is a desire of the Syrian new leadership of development,
advancement and looking ahead to a new, progressive future.''
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad is seen as a modernizer, and Israelis hope he will
moderate his father's views and reopen peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak told Israel television he hoped Bashar
''would bring Syria to openness with the world ... and peace in the
Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks between the countries broke down in January because
of disagreements over the scope of Israel's territorial
concessions. Assad's son and designated heir, Bashar Assad, was
expected to focus on consolidating his power, making it unlikely
peace talks would resume anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin, however, expressed hope that talks could resume sooner
with the help of American mediators. He said that after the
funeral, it would be appropriate to begin building contacts between
Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It won't be too early tomorrow, or the day after tomorrow,''
Beilin said. ''It won't be easy, because usually a new regime wants
to establish itself first and wait a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''But I'm not sure whether now we can afford to wait
too long, and whether it is going to serve the national interest of
Syria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
