<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Bids Final Farewell to Assad  </HEADLINE>
By HAMZA HENDAWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- They sobbed and wailed. Some fainted
under the combined effect of grief and heat. Others climbed trees
and light poles to take a last look, or sought to ease their
anguish with softly whispered prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians on Tuesday paid their last respects to Hafez Assad, the
man who ruled them with an iron grip for 30 years. Scores of world
leaders attended the funeral, which took a grueling 12 hours to
complete, beginning in the capital, Damascus, and ending 125 miles
to the northwest in Assad's home village of Qardaha.
</P>
<P>
   An enormous funeral procession snaked slowly through the streets
of the capital, bearing the body of the late president, the only
leader many in this isolated nation have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's body was then flown to the coastal city of Latakia,
where police struggled to keep the mourning crowds at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Throngs of men, women and children lined the 10-mile stretch of
road from Latakia to Qardaha, some of them having camped overnight
to ensure an unobstructed view of Assad's flag-draped coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where are you going? Take us with you!'' shouted a woman
wearing a black robe and white head scarf. ''May God have mercy on
your soul,'' she said, as the last of a long convoy of cars
disappeared from sight and into Qardaha.
</P>
<P>
   Assad was buried in the village alongside his eldest son, Basil,
who had been Assad's first choice as successor before he died in a
1994 car crash.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners had begun trickling into Damascus at first light
Tuesday. A brass band played a funeral dirge as the procession
crawled slowly through the capital's streets.
</P>
<P>
   A sea of mourners walked the cortege route, shouting chants and
waving placards with portraits of Assad. A chain of presidential
guards and policemen linked hands to prevent people from flinging
themselves toward the coffin, which was borne by a gun carriage and
covered in the black, red and white Syrian flag.
</P>
<P>
   At one point mourners, overcome with grief, attempted to break
through the security cordon. The troops pushed them back, but not
before the mourners brought down part of a concrete fence.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral was carried live on Syrian TV and throughout much of
the Middle East on other Arab channels.
</P>
<P>
   Many mourners arrived in organized groups, with union colleagues
and office co-workers joining in the ceremonies together. Each
group marched in turn around a traffic circle, chanting at the
command of a group leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''We dedicate our lives to the president!'' they cried.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
