<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Nuclear Secrets Missing  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said Tuesday
he's ''outraged'' at the latest security lapse at the Los Alamos
weapons lab, but that he doubts espionage or theft was involved in
the loss of top-secret computer drives that contain nuclear
secrets, saying they likely were misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the drives, which contained information
about how to dismantle both U.S. and Russian nuclear devices,
prompted sharp criticism in Congress and a call for renewed
hearings on security in the Energy Department's nuclear programs,
especially the weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who spent most of last year defusing a security flap
involving fired Los Alamos scientist Wen Ho Lee, came under sharp
criticism Tuesday for the latest incident, although he apparently
didn't know about it until a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''This incident occurred on his watch. He'll have to be held
accountable,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., chairman of the Armed
Services Committee. Warner said his committee planned a hearing
Thursday on the missing nuclear material and both Richardson and
Los Alamos lab director John Browne were to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he was ''outraged by the security lapses that
have taken place'' and that he expects some officials at Los Alamos
to be disciplined, possibly within days, for not notifying the
Energy Department promptly about the missing computer drives.
</P>
<P>
   The drives were found missing from a metal container in a highly
secure vault in the Los Alamos lab's ''X Division'' complex where
nuclear bomb designers work. The discovery was made late in the
evening on May 7 as scientists sought to secure them from a massive
wildfire threatening the lab complex. Energy Department officials
did not learn of the disappearance for 24 days, until June 1.
</P>
<P>
   During that time both Richardson and his top ''security czar,''
retired Air Force Gen. Eugene Habiger, flew to Los Alamos because
of the wildfires. Neither, however, was given a hint that nuclear
secrets may have been compromised, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm most concerned about the failure of the lab to promptly
notify ... when these potential (security) breaches took place. ...
The lab is going to have to have some good explanations,''
Richardson told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The two drives, about the size of a deck of cards and each
containing identical information, were used by the Nuclear
Emergency Search Team, or NEST, which is trained to respond to
nuclear accidents or terrorist acts. The drives, which can be used
in a laptop computer, contain highly technical nuclear weapons data
needed to disarm and dismantle nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of such sensitive top-secret nuclear files
opened the way Tuesday for renewed attacks from Republicans in
Congress on the Clinton administration's safeguarding of nuclear
materials -- an issue that dominated much of last year amid
criticism that the administration botched an investigation at Los
Alamos into the alleged loss of nuclear secrets to China in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Alamos scientist, Wen Ho Lee, had for three years been
suspected of giving information about nuclear warheads to China,
although no evidence has ever surfaced linking him to any
espionage. Lee, fired from Los Alamos in March, 1999, was arrested
last December and charged with illegally copying secret computer
files. The files have never been found and he is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest security matter, Richardson said Tuesday he doubts
that espionage or theft was involved and that his security and
counterintelligence experts ''believe that these drives have been
misplaced'' during the ''strain and confusion'' caused by last
month's wildfires that destroyed thousands of acres and hundreds of
homes in Los Alamos, threatening the lab itself.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers are not as convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., a member of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, said there was ''physical evidence to suggest theft,''
but he declined to elaborate. Kyl, a sharp critic of DOE's security
of nuclear materials, called the lost computer drives an
''unacceptable security breach.''
</P>
<P>
   Habiger, tapped last year by Richardson to be the department's
''security czar,'' said Tuesday only 26 people had authority to
enter the vault where the missing drives were kept so that on
moments notice they could be available to the nuclear weapons
response teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are dedicated loyal Americans,'' Habiger told a House
Commerce subcommittee hearing, adding that in his judgment the
missing data likely was lost or misplaced, and not stolen. Habiger
led the weeklong search and investigation at Los Alamos last week
after DOE was notified of the missing material.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee
http://www.senate.gov/~armed--services/
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory http://www.lanl.gov/external/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1714 </TRAILER>
