<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia: Peace Plan Needs Review  </HEADLINE>
By ABEBE ANDUALEM
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Fighting with Eritrea has subsided
in the Horn of Africa war after three days of heavy clashes,
Ethiopia said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Government spokeswoman Selome Taddesse said only minor
skirmishes were reported at the eastern Bure front, 25 miles from
the Eritrean port city of Assab. The spokeswoman's claims could not
be independently confirmed, nor was there any word on the progress
of fighting in western Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Most fighting on the eastern and western fronts occurs during
the late afternoon because of the searing heat, which regularly
reaches 122 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia said Monday that its army was advancing toward the key
western town of Teseney, which Eritrean forces retook in a fierce
12-hour battle last week.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Eritrean troops have been killed, wounded or
captured during the latest offensive, said a statement issued
Monday by the Ethiopian government. Ethiopia on Sunday recaptured
Guluj, 20 miles south of Teseney, and has seized key positions
between the two towns, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eritrean capital, Asmara, there was no comment on the
Ethiopian claims.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin arrived
back in the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, following two weeks of
peace talks in Algiers brokered by the Organization of African
Unity. He was to brief Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and other
Ethiopian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia announced Saturday it had agreed in principle with an
OAU-drafted peace plan. A day later, however, Selome said the
proposals had to be discussed by the country's leaders because they
involved ''such major issues as territorial integrity and
sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   The OAU has given Ethiopia until this weekend to accept or
reject the peace plan, which calls for a cease-fire, U.N.
peacekeepers to monitor the border and outside demarcation of the
contested Ethiopian-Eritrean border.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia launched an offensive against Eritrea on May 12,
re-igniting a war that has already cost the lives of thousands of
soldiers and civilians on both sides. The latest round of fighting
has displaced up to 1 million Eritreans, according to international
aid agencies in Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eritrean capital, the U.N. World Food Program said
Tuesday there was enough emergency food in Eritrea to sustain the
country for two months, but not enough trucks to transport the food
to the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Rowe, a WFP spokesman, said the agency was preparing a
$60 million aid request to donors, including an appeal for funds to
purchase 35 trucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
