<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother gives up baby in innovative program to protect infants  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TROY, N.Y. (AP) - A 20-year-old mother who gave birth to a boy
tried to give him something more hours later: a better life.
</P>
<P>
   In an innovative program, the mother gave up her child under a
program aimed at encouraging parents to turn over their newborns in
a ''safe haven'' rather than risk neglect or death as in some
recent cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't know what to do. They're in a panic,'' said
Rensselaer County District Attorney Kenneth Bruno in a news
conference Tuesday after the child was turned over to county
authorities. ''This is the thing to do. It's the only responsible
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day the state Senate run by Bruno's father,
Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, R-Brunswick, unanimously
approved a bill that would do much the same thing as the county
program. Those who abandon newborns in safe settings like hospitals
wouldn't face prosecution. The bill comes after reports of a few
distraught young mothers who abandoned babies in trash bins partly
out of fear of arrest or other problems.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was born in Troy at 11:30 a.m. in Seton Health-St.
Mary's Hospital. Under the county program, a mother can give up
most rights to a child within 72 hours of birth anonymously if the
mother chooses. From there, county social services workers took
over. The child would then enter the foster care system and become
available for adoption, Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   If the mother later protests, saying the decision was made under
the duress after giving birth, she can seek custody of the child.
But at that point, the decision would be made the county Department
of Social Services.
</P>
<P>
   In May, prosecutors, hospital administrators and social service
officials from nine counties around Albany unveiled Project Safe
Haven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
