<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Backs Nigeria Debt Relief  </HEADLINE>
By GILBERT DA COSTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- The United States will support debt relief
for Nigeria, where the restoration of civilian rule has created a
''window of opportunity,'' Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, who concluded a two-day visit to the impoverished West
African nation on Monday, said the United States would back
''generous'' debt rescheduling this year by the Paris Club of donor
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Provided Nigeria makes ''significant progress on meaningful
financial and economic reforms,'' the United States would in
subsequent years urge the international financial community to
reduce the country's $30 billion foreign debt, Summers said. Among
the Nigerian reforms sought by the United States is budget
reallocation to ensure that savings from debt relief would be
channeled into education and health.
</P>
<P>
   Summers also noted the need to move ahead with Nigeria's planned
privatization of state assets and to establish the rule of law in a
nation where ethnic and religious fighting is endemic and
corruption is rife.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nigeria's economic challenges are very great,'' Summers said.
''But I believe the democratic opportunity Nigeria now has provides
the best window of opportunity Nigeria has enjoyed in many years.''
</P>
<P>
   President Olusegun Obasanjo's election last year ended 15 years
of military rule in Nigeria, which remains desperately poor despite
the country's status as the world's sixth-largest oil producer.
</P>
<P>
   Summers met with Obasanjo as well as the central bank governor
and other top officials while in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was encouraged by the indications that the president and the
vice president gave with regard to their policy intentions, but
what is going to be crucial is their effectiveness in carrying
through those policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers left Monday for Tanzania, the next leg of an African
tour which will also take in South Africa, Mozambique and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   He cut short his planned three-day Nigeria visit to let
government and labor leaders meet. The two sides were working to
resolve a five-day national strike touched off by climbing fuel
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders called off the work stoppage Tuesday after the
government reduced a 50 percent hike in the cost of petroleum
products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
