<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man freed 23 years after doctor's murder angry, bitter, and thankful </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. (AP) - For the second time in his life, Lawrence
Simmons has had murder charges against him dropped.
</P>
<P>
   But after spending 23 years behind bars for a killing he insists
he didn't commit, Simmons is angry, bitter, and thankful the
justice system he once scorned has freed him.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old Paterson man was released Monday after the
Passaic County Prosecutor's Office declined to seek a fourth trial
in the 1977 beating death of Dr. David Doktor, a prominent Paterson
physician who was on his way to an emergency call.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court overturned Simmons' murder conviction in 1995,
and two subsequent trials ended in hung juries. The prosecutor's
office declined to try him again, saying he had already served more
time in prison than he could get at sentencing if convicted again.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in custody on $500,000 bail since then, and was also
serving a 15-year term for an unrelated mugging that occurred the
same night as the doctor's killing. Simmons says he's innocent of
that crime, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want the public to know that Lawrence Simmons did not and
would not kill or take the life of another human being,'' Simmons
said at a news conference flanked by relatives at his lawyers'
office. ''It's not in me. I want the doctor's family to know I am
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand their anger. Just like the doctor's family are
victims, I am a victim, too,'' Simmons said. ''I spent 23 years in
jail for a crime I did not commit. I lost a lot of family members
and friends who passed away without the chance to say goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his lawyers would not say if he plans civil litigation
against anyone regarding the case.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons spent his first night of freedom meeting nieces and
nephews who were born while he was behind bars, and eating a dinner
of chicken, macaroni salad and potatoes his 70-year-old mother,
Louvenia Simmons, made for him.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons previously worked as a welder, and learned how to strip
floors while in prison, but does not know what he wants to do for a
living now that he's free.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm gonna work not one, but two jobs,'' he said. ''I have a
lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons saved most of his anger for the state's star witness in
the crime, David R. Wilson, who got immunity in the case and
testified against him, only to later recant his testimony. Wilson
is currently in jail on unrelated charges, as is co-defendant
Donald Phillips, said Simmons' lawyer, Miles Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson admitted acting as the lookout during the attack, and
testified that Simmons kicked and punched the doctor and ripped the
wallet from his pocket as Phillips beat the doctor with a pipe.
</P>
<P>
   But Simmons said his clothing, including his shoes, had no blood
on them, while the other two men were covered with blood and one
was wearing the doctor's hat at the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he was at his sister Wanda's house when the doctor
was killed. Steven Brizek, Passaic County's senior assistant
prosecutor who handled two of Simmons' trials in the Doktor case,
noted that Simmons' sister lived with Phillips, adding the men had
ample time to have committed the killing that night.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he suspects police wanted to implicate him in
Doktor's killing because previous murder charges against Simmons
involving the death of his brother were dropped by an appeals
court.
</P>
<P>
   He said his brother, Morris Addison, was killed by a police
officer in Paterson in 1974, and police charged Simmons with felony
murder in connection with his death. He said he believes
investigators told Wilson, ''Lawrence Simmons got away with murder
once,'' and influenced Wilson to implicate him in Doktor's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Brizek said Simmons and two accomplices had robbed a milk store
and were fleeing when police shot his brother. Brizek said the
felony murder conviction was reversed after judges ruled that an
accomplice cannot be charged with murder in such a situation, but
noted that assault and robbery charges were allowed to stand.
</P>
<P>
   He said Simmons had ample time to come forward with allegations
of police misconduct in the investigation since 1977, but chose not
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court overturned Simmons' murder conviction in 1995
because some transcripts of jury selection proceedings were
missing, and were needed to determine whether racial bias played a
role in the composition of the jury, which was predominantly white,
Feinstein said. Simmons is black.
</P>
<P>
   ''If one combs the record, one will not find a single jury which
has unanimously concluded that Lawrence Simmons is not guilty of
murdering Dr. Doktor,'' Brizek told a judge Monday before agreeing
not to seek a fourth trial. In his 1996 retrial, the vote was
8-to-4 for conviction. In 1998, it was 9-to-3 for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   He said people should focus on the 64-year-old Doktor, who was
answering a telephone call in the middle of the night, asking him
to substitute for another doctor who couldn't make it to a hospital
to care for an elderly woman who had just suffered a stroke, when
he was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let us remember that in that precious moment when all of his
attention was focused on saving a life, his was taken from him,''
Brizek told the judge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1735 </TRAILER>
