<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Clips to 3rd Place on Nielsen  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Riding the instant success of ''Survivor,'' CBS
had a solid week in the prime-time television ratings and ABC
learned how far it could sink when it has to pre-empt Regis
Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   With 18 million viewers, more people watched the strangers
testing their survival skills on a rat-infested island last week
than tuned in to any of the first three games of the NBA Finals,
Nielsen Media Research said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor'' even beat ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' in
head-to-head competition on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, the season's ratings leader, slipped to third place for the
week, primarily because it devoted three nights of prime-time to
the Stanley Cup hockey finals between Dallas and New Jersey. It was
the network's worst week since December, before ''Millionaire''
joined the regular schedule.
</P>
<P>
   By hockey's standards, the matchup did well: Thursday night's
long, tense overtime struggle drew the highest household ratings
for a Stanley Cup finals game in 20 years, according to ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thursday's average audience for the hockey game was less
than a quarter of what ABC could have expected from ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's highest-rated show of the week was its concert special
with Britney Spears from Hawaii. Its effort at duplicating ABC's
game show success with ''Chance of a Lifetime'' fell flat, however.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had a respectable showing with its summer series,
''M.Y.O.B.,'' while ABC cancelled its poor-performing ''Clerks''
after two showings.
</P>
<P>
   NBC averaged 10.66 million viewers in prime-time last week,
narrowly edging CBS' 10.61 million viewers. CBS' ratings were
slightly higher (7.6 rating, 14 share) than NBC's (7.5, 14), which
indicates that more CBS viewers were watching alone.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had 9.3 million viewers on average (6.3 rating, 11 share),
Fox had 6.4 million viewers (4.3, 8), UPN had 3.7 million (2.4, 4
share), the WB had 2.4 million (1.7, 3) and Pax TV had 1.2 million
(0.9, 2).
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' dominated the evening news ratings race
with 9.4 million viewers (7.0 rating, 16 share). ABC's ''World News
Tonight'' had 8.1 million viewers (6.0, 14), and the ''CBS Evening
News'' had 7.4 million viewers (5.8, 13).
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of June 5-11, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were:
</P>
<P>
   ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 16.3; ''Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Tuesday), ABC, 15.8; ''Survivor,''
CBS, 11.7; ''48 Hours'' (Monday), CBS, 11.2; ''NBA Finals Game 3:
L.A. Lakers at Indiana,'' NBC, 10.7; ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' (Wednesday), ABC, 10.6; ''NBA Finals Game 1: Indiana
at L.A. Lakers,'' NBC, 10.5; ''Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS,
10.3; ''60 Minutes,'' CBS, 10.1; ''NBA Finals Game 2: Indiana at
L.A. Lakers,'' NBC, 9.9.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1736 </TRAILER>
