<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 31 charged in marriage fraud ring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A ring that found American wives for
Pakistani men looking for U.S. residency was broken up Tuesday with
the indictment of 31 people on marriage fraud, federal authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials identified 28 fraudulent marriages linked
to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Among those charged were 17 men from Pakistan, seven American
citizen ''wives'' and seven people who allegedly helped arranged
the marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our two-year investigation culminated in the dismantling of
the largest fraud ring we've ever seen in the Buffalo district,''
Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The women were paid to marry the men and the couples would not
live together after marriage. The wives would file for divorce once
their husbands received permanent residency cards, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This investigation shows the ends to which foreign nationals
desiring American citizenship will go to attain it,'' U.S. Attorney
Denise O'Donnell said. ''It is deeply disturbing that U.S. citizens
are so willing to further these illegal schemes by entering into
sham marriages and lying under oath to government authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also led to charges of food-stamp trafficking
against six individuals, including two allegedly involved in the
marriage scheme. Authorities said the defendants were either owners
or employees of Rochester convenience stores and purchased $177,985
in food stamps for $65,150 between May 1999 and June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Those charged in the marriage fraud ring could face prison
sentences of up to 10 years if convicted. Food stamp fraud carries
a maximum prison term of five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
