<HEADLINE> Woody Allen wins as landmarks panel rejects East Side apartment tower </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Woody Allen scored a hit in his off-screen role
as a neighborhood defender Tuesday when the city Landmarks
Preservation Commission rejected a 17-story building he had
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very pleasantly surprised,'' Allen said after the
11-member commission unanimously turned down the proposed apartment
tower on Madison Avenue in the Carnegie Hill Historic District.
''I'm so used to losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen testified against the project in February and distributed
a 3-minute video to commission members.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've tried to make New York City look like the most beautiful
and the warmest, the most romantic city in the world, and to some
degree I've succeeded,'' he said then. ''Invariably when I'm
filming, I come to Carnegie Hill to film because there are very few
areas anywhere on the island where I can really present the city in
the way that I want to world to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said on Tuesday that he was pessimistic about preservation
battles but ''if you love the city you really have to try all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When I made the movie 'Manhattan' we went over the city and
shot in many, many places and had quite a few good vistas,'' Allen
said. ''Now a lot of those vistas don't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Allen's East Side neighbors cheered when commission
Chairwoman Jennifer Raab called the proposed Madison Avenue
building too tall for the site and said it ''should not and will
not be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen stood silently in the back of the City Hall hearing room,
not cracking a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked the commission afterward, saying it ''really did act
with enormous responsibility not just to the people of Carnegie
Hill but to the entire city, everyone who lives here.''
</P>
<P>
   Developer Cary Tamarkin said in a prepared statement: ''I
respect the views articulated by the members of the commission, and
I look forward to working with the commission and members of the
community in the months ahead as we develop a new design for the
building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
