<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attack came out of nowhere  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The water came out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of guys with what looked like water bottles started
splashing me, catching me on my arms, my back, my side. I kept
turning to get away, and moving toward the Central Park South exit,
assuming my friend Stephanie was right behind me.
</P>
<P>
   It was hot and sticky Sunday, so the first splash was actually
kind of cooling. I was annoyed, but not really angry.
</P>
<P>
   But the guys started aiming at my face, splashing over and over
again until I was blinded. I couldn't see where they were coming
from anymore, and I couldn't see Stephanie - until I heard her
scream my name and break through the group of guys who had
surrounded and groped her.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie agreed Tuesday to have her comments published on
condition that her last name be withheld.
</P>
<P>
   We had been on the Fifth Avenue side of Central Park for most of
the afternoon, watching the Puerto Rican Day Parade. And aside from
the pushing and shoving among the massive crowd, we hadn't seen any
rowdiness.
</P>
<P>
   We moved into the park in the late afternoon to get away from
the parade spectators, and were making our way to the West Side,
running into acquaintances, and stopping to people-watch.
</P>
<P>
   Hormones were definitely running high in the park. ''Guys and
girls were flirting, but there wasn't anything disorderly going on
from what I saw,'' Stephanie recalled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   We meant to exit on Central Park West but got turned around and
ended up near Central Park South close to 6 p.m. There were a lot
of blocked-off walkways and police along Fifth Avenue, but when we
got near the south entrance, there were no officers in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of ironic this (the assaults) happened at the
entrance, a place you would think there would be more police,''
Stephanie said. ''It seemed police were mostly concerned people
would break through barricades and join in the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   As we neared the entrance, we heard shouting coming from a crowd
of guys.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw water going up in the air,'' Stephanie said. ''I was too
far away to assess what exactly was going on, but I didn't want to
walk through that area just because you never know what could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a guy tapped her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me, 'Don't go through there. Trust me, don't go
through there,''' Stephanie said.
</P>
<P>
   We aimed for the side wall of the park, me in front and
Stephanie behind, assuming the guys would be too busy bothering
some other women to notice us. We were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently, I caught somebody's attention because one guy
started pointing at me and yelling 'Yo, yo, yo, yo, yo,'''
Stephanie recalled, still shaken two days later.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before I knew it, I was surrounded by what seemed to be 20
guys, all pouring water on me, and I was trying to push through.
They were coming at me from all directions, and they were grabbing
my butt, groping my butt, and I was screaming and I was trying to
get through, trying to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys had separated us, so I couldn't see Stephanie and she
couldn't see me. I was lucky; the guys around me didn't try to
touch me, and I was able to keep moving forward. The ones around
Stephanie had her trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was scared. I felt like I had no control, everything
happened so fast but yet it felt like slow motion,'' she said. ''I
didn't know what would end up happening; that was the scariest part
of all.''
</P>
<P>
   She managed to push through and get to where I was. I was
stunned at her appearance - she was soaked. Her shorts, her tank
top, her hair, there wasn't a dry spot anywhere on her
six-foot-tall frame.
</P>
<P>
   We left the park then, heading back uptown on the train. It
wasn't until we got to the subway station at Columbus Circle that
we saw any police officers.
</P>
<P>
   On the train, we kept talking about what had just happened, how
it was the kind of situation that could easily lead to some woman
really getting hurt. Then, on the news that night, we heard that it
had.
</P>
<P>
   ''They could have pushed me to the ground like they did those
other girls,'' said Stephanie. ''Seeing the report on the news, I
just knew it was the same guys and I just feel fortunate that
nothing worse happened to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1745 </TRAILER>
