<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians Reopen Talks  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Faced with a self-imposed mid-September
deadline, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators resumed their
slow-moving talks Tuesday under U.S. auspices.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is an accord settling the future of Jerusalem and
determining the dimensions of a state the Palestinians are expected
to establish on Israeli-held land.
</P>
<P>
   The American hosts declined to say whether the first round of
talks in more than two weeks was productive, and Israeli and
Palestinian officials, at U.S. direction, declined to characterize
the discussions held at two American air force bases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously there's not much time between now and September, and
I think as evidenced by the fact that the parties are here in the
Washington area discussing the issues, they take it very
seriously,'' the White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, U.S. mediator Aaron D. Miller met separately with
each side. Then the Israelis and Palestinians met face-to-face,
without American participation. They also canceled a planned
three-way evening meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees, water problems and a promised Israeli pullback this
month on the West Bank also were on the agenda at Andrews Air Force
Base in suburban Maryland and at Bolling Air Force Base in
southeast Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was due to fly here on
Wednesday to meet with President Clinton Thursday at the White
House. He is expected to meet also with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO's representative in Washington, said
''we hope that this round of negotiations will lead to an agreement
on a framework'' for an overall settlement and that U.S. mediation
efforts will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock ticking down, and President Clinton eager for an
accord in the final months of his second term, American mediators
were due to take a more forceful role to try to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have not even
begun official discussions of Jerusalem, part of which Arafat is
demanding as a capital, and have made little headway on other
thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
   The talks broke down two weeks ago amid violence on the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after talking to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in
Jerusalem and Arafat in the West Bank town of Ramallah, Albright
said they wanted the United States to ''call audibles'' -- a
reference to football quarterbacks calling plays at the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But before flying Monday to Damascus and the funeral of Syrian
President Hafez Assad, whose own negotiations with Israel were
mired in disagreement, Albright said she did not expect a
breakthrough soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issues are difficult and complex and will take time to
resolve,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message to the negotiators, Lockhart said Monday, was
that ''time is short. We're at a critical moment in this process,
and all the parties need to understand the importance of working
together to bridge these remaining differences, as difficult as
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is trying to prepare the Israeli people for more
concessions to Arafat. He has already offered suburbs of Jerusalem
and said he would carry out this month's promised pullback on the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Israeli and Palestinian leaders have accused the other
of foot-dragging.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is faced with severe political problems at home, with
opponents trying to force new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Albright have publicly expressed their support for
Palestinian ''aspirations,'' without specifying what they had in
mind or what they thought Israel should do in the Palestinians'
behalf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1750 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0138 </DOCNO>
