<HEADLINE> New tests all negative for EEE, West Nile-like virus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The first batch of mosquitoes tested this
season showed no trace of either the Eastern Equine or West
Nile-like strains of the encephalitis virus, state environmental
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As of June 13, 1,493 mosquitoes had been trapped and tested from
12 sites statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito traps placed by the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment
Station in 73 locations will be collected on a 10-day rotation.
Trapping began June 1 and will continue through early fall.
</P>
<P>
   As of June 9, 27 birds had also tested negative for the West
Nile-like strain of the virus, the state Department of
Environmental Protection said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, New York announced that two crows tested positive for
the West Nile-like strain of the virus. Another crow tested
positive for the virus in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The virus has not caused any human sickness in Connecticut, but
last year infected 72 people in New York, killing seven.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was found last season in two mosquitoes trapped on the
Greenwich/Stamford town line and in thousands of birds in New York,
New Jersey and Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
