<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Acquitted in Irish Gun Case  </HEADLINE>
By TERRY SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Three men were convicted Tuesday of
shipping weapons to Ireland, but acquitted of the most serious
charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   Conor Claxton, Martin Mullan and Anthony Smyth were acquitted on
charges of shipping weapons to terrorists and conspiracy to maim or
murder persons in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   If they had been convicted of the more serious charges, they
could have faced up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was read, Claxton turned to his family and
supporters in the courtroom, smiled and gave a thumbs-up. He then
hugged his attorney, Fred Haddad.
</P>
<P>
   Claxton, a 27-year-old Northern Ireland resident; Mullan, a
30-year-old Philadelphia handyman; and Smyth, a 43-year-old car
salesman in Weston, a Fort Lauderdale suburb, were arrested in
July. All three are all Roman Catholic natives of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   They were accused of buying guns and ammunition in Florida and
then mailing them to Ireland for the Irish Republican Army, which
has waged a long battle against the British government in Northern
Ireland. Police intercepted 23 packages containing 122 guns and
other weapons allegedly mailed by the group.
</P>
<P>
   Claxton, an admitted IRA member and the group's leader, was
convicted on 39 counts, including using a false passport to
facilitate terrorism, weapons smuggling and conspiracy. He faces a
maximum sentence of 275 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth was convicted on 31 counts and faces a maximum penalty of
116 years; Mullan was convicted of 10 counts and faces a maximum 63
years.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Richard Scruggs said that he thinks the jurors may
have been influenced by recent developments in Northern Ireland,
where the IRA has agreed to put aside its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will never second-guess what a jury did,'' Scruggs said.
</P>
<P>
   During the monthlong trial, Claxton insisted that only he knew
about the gun smuggling and that he didn't know it was illegal. He
testified that militant Irish-Americans pushed him to buy weapons
because they feared Catholics -- few of whom are allowed to own guns
in Northern Ireland -- could be left at the mercy of the Protestant
paramilitary and police forces under the recent peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   The defense maintained that the purchases could be considered
self-defense given the years of bloodshed in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also said that Mullan didn't know the packages he
mailed for Claxton during a family vacation contained weapons, and
that Smyth thought he was acting as a middleman for legitimate gun
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth's fiancee, Siobhan Brown, was also arrested and pleaded
guilty to one of 33 counts against her. She awaits sentencing this
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1755 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transformation of Camden thoroughfare on schedule  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
Associated Press Writer
AP Photos TN101-102
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - When Apostle James Treadwell turned the
French Quarter strip club into Gatekeepers Fellowship Church 10
years ago, he envisioned it as the first step in the transformation
of seedy Admiral Wilson Boulevard, which cuts through the city and
leads to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's where we felt our mission was to begin,'' Treadwell
said outside his church Tuesday. ''Change the building, change the
reputation, change the look of the boulevard. Through our prayers,
through our presence. Starting with one hopeful sign in the middle
of the prostitution, the porn places.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the dilapidated strip clubs, motels and gas stations and
most of the billboards hawking nude dancers and X-rated movies are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   In their place will be a tree-lined park along the Cooper River
with picnic and play areas, a fishing platform, a bicycle path and
an exercise loop. The boulevard itself is being resurfaced and
landscaped.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman's goal was for the project, being done by
the state and the Delaware River Port Authority, to be finished by
the end of July, when the Republican National Convention begins
across the river in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The convention's opening ceremonies will be held on Camden's
riverfront, and delegate and corporate events will be held at the
Thomas Kean New Jersey State Aquarium and the Sony E-Center. Also,
many of the delegates will stay in southern New Jersey hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't afford to pass up the chance to put New Jersey's best
foot forward,'' Whitman said in March 1999, when the project was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Work is on schedule, Joe Diemer, spokesman for the port
authority, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The port authority has reached agreements with owners of nearly
40 of the 44 properties on the south side of the highway, where the
park will be located. Many of those buildings have been demolished
and work on the road should be finished by the end of June. Sod or
grass seed will soon be put down where the buildings once stood.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd like to have a good deal of that south side green within
the next several weeks,'' Diemer said, adding that the whole park
will be finished by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the north side of the road, is ''slower and not as
exciting, but integral to the project,'' Diemer said. The state and
port authority are developing a plan to create a business zone
there, possibly including an industrial park and new homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The north side has real significant economic potential on the
highway leading right into Philadelphia,'' Diemer said.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements still need to be reached with several south side
property owners on prices to be paid for their properties, Diemer
said, but no one has made any legal challenges to the process.
</P>
<P>
   The port authority and Gatekeepers Fellowship Church reached an
agreement Monday for the port authority to take title to the church
and demolish it. Treadwell and his 200 members will move across the
highway to a former car dealership.
</P>
<P>
   No one is happier about that than Treadwell.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't look at it like we've lost,'' he said. ''We look at
it like we've really gained. We wanted to change the reputation of
the city and the boulevard. When people came by here they used to
see pornography, prostitution and addiction. Now, they'll be able
to say, 'Wow. It's changing around here.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it would be very, very hard for prostitution and
drug traffic to continue here because the climate has changed,'' he
said. ''I believe this beautification has raised the attitude of
this city, also raised the hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1755 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Rises 58; Nasdaq Up 83  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Tuesday as investors seized on the
latest retail sales report as evidence that the economy is slowing
just enough to persuade the Federal Reserve to leave interest rates
unchanged at its next meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' optimism over the state of the economy helped the
market break out of a slump that started after Wall Street
investment firm Sanford Bernstein cut its rating and earnings
estimates for Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 57.63 to close at
10,621.84. The blue-chip index recovered from an early loss of more
than 70 points, and without Hewlett-Packard's steep loss would have
closed at least 35 points higher.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 23.44 at 1,469.44, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 83.15 at 3,851.06.
</P>
<P>
   In a session that saw the market struggle to find direction,
stocks rose after Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan applauded the use of
technology to enhance the productivity of American workers.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks before the New York Association for Business
Economics, Greenspan said much of the improvement in productivity
was due to basic changes in the economy, rather than temporary
factors that could disappear.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan did not discuss interest rates, many investors
took his comments as a sign that the Fed is growing more
comfortable with the pace of the economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   The latest sign that the economy is returning to a more
sustainable pace came from the Commerce Department, which said
retail sales fell for the second month in a row in May, the latest
sign that six interest rate increases by the Fed are successfully
slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, revised figures showed that retail sales fell 0.6
percent in April, much weaker than the government estimated one
month ago. The combination of two weaker than expected months at
the nation's stores allowed investors to hope that the Fed might
hold rates steady at its next meeting on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Fed is finished for the year,'' said Don Selkin,
chief investment strategist at Joseph Gunnar in New York. Selkin
pointed out that May economic figures don't reflect the Fed's last
rate increase, a half-percentage point boost on May 16 that drove
rates to the highest level since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will see more evidence of a slowdown, and with that
evidence in hand, the Fed really won't be able to justify raising
rates any higher,'' Selkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said investors are also concerned that the
hoped-for slowdown, which the Fed hopes will prevent inflation from
rearing up, will eventually hurt corporate earnings. On Tuesday,
investors embraced so-called defensive stocks -- those whose profits
aren't significantly affected by fluctuations in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Merck rose $3.50 to $73.438 and Warner Lambert rose $2.813 to
$125.875.
</P>
<P>
   Also, financial stocks rose on the hope that rates will soon
stabilize. Banks and brokerages are especially vulnerable to
interest rate fluctuations. Lehman Brothers rose $1.438 to $86.625
and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter rose $2.563 to $83.375.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell $7 to $119, pulling the Dow lower. Sanford
Bernstein lowered its rating on Hewlett-Packard to a ''market
perform'' from ''market outperform'' and reduced earnings
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The market's harsh punishment of Hewlett-Packard indicated that
investors remain nervous about corporate profits, which are
generally threatened by rising interest rates, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any kind of bad news you see out there will be taken very
badly by the equity markets,'' said Gary Dugan, head of global
equity at J.P. Morgan Investment Management. ''The pressures are
quite enormous on the corporate sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 910.81 million
shares, compared with 751.95 million at the same time Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.24 to 513.75.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.4 percent.
Germany's DAX index rose 0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 gained
0.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.3 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
