<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cop admits lying to Louima investigators  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A police officer on trial in Brooklyn federal
court admitted Tuesday he lied to protect himself and other
officers instead of helping authorities catch the patrolmen who
tortured Abner Louima in a precinct bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''You lied because you didn't want to give information that
would get another cop in trouble ... because you didn't want to end
up a witness in the Louima case, right?'' prosecutor Alan Vinegrad
asked defendant Francisco Rosario on cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes,'' the officer replied.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario, 35, took the stand in his own defense against charges
he misled investigators by not telling them he saw Officer Justin
Volpe throw a battered, half-naked Louima into a holding cell
following the infamous 1997 attack in Brooklyn's 70th Precinct. The
defendant was booking his own prisoner at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe pleaded guilty to sodomizing the handcuffed prisoner with
a broken broomstick in a fit of rage. Another officer, Charles
Schwarz, was convicted at an earlier trial of holding down Louima
during the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario faces charges that he and his partner conspired to make
false statements - part of what prosecutors say was a ''blue wall
of silence'' surrounding the case. If convicted, he faces up to
five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant told the jury Tuesday that a union delegate with
the powerful Patrolmen's Benevolent Association pressured him to
keep quiet when investigators began questioning potential police
witnesses. Asked about the testimony, PBA spokesman Joseph Mancini
refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario testified that his supervisor, Sgt. James Yee, told him,
''Keep me out of this'' - a claim Yee denies. He also said he was
motivated by fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like my world was tumbling,'' he said. ''I was
afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has argued Rosario's decision to first tell FBI
agents he was not inside the holding cell area was a mistake, not a
federal offense. He testified that he tried to set the record
straight in a follow-up interview, admitting he had seen an officer
toss Louima into a cell, then curse at the Haitian immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought once I came clean, that I would be OK,'' Rosario
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosario said the officer wasn't Volpe, which prosecutors
allege was another lie.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Vinegrad sought to portray Rosario as a
corrupt cop who put his own interests ahead of the helpless victim
of a vicious assault.
</P>
<P>
   ''You just thought about yourself, right?'' Vinegrad asked in
one exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You didn't give a thought to Mr. Louima?''
</P>
<P>
   ''At that point, yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
