<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pirro's defense rests without calling witnesses  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - The defense suddenly rested Tuesday
without calling any witnesses in the criminal tax evasion case
against millionaire lobbyist Albert Pirro, husband of Westchester
County's celebrity district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Al Pirro does not wish to call any witnesses, alive or
dead,'' said defense attorney Gustave Newman.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, at the start of the court session, obviously
surprised the jurors, who immediately started buzzing among
themselves as federal Judge Barrington Parker spoke to the lawyers
privately. At least one of the expected defense witnesses was in
court, ready to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro had pledged that the trial would address what he claimed
was the political motive behind his prosecution - holding back his
wife's career. But there was no mention of that at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro and his accountant brother Anthony - whose defense also
rested - are accused of conspiring to hide more than $1 million of
Albert's income as business writeoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The jury had heard four weeks of testimony from prosecution
witnesses who collectively offered a detailed look at Pirro's
lavish lifestyle, much of which was written off as tax deductions
for his many companies. Such luxuries as a $123,000 Ferrari, a
$13,000 rug and home security gates that cost $45,000 were personal
items, bought by Pirro's businesses, that should have been treated
as income, the prosecution said.
</P>
<P>
   An Internal Revenue Service agent who testified for five days
said Pirro underpaid taxes by $412,518.
</P>
<P>
   The defense acknowledged that Pirro's tax returns were flawed
but insisted that there was no criminal intent, that Pirro left
such matters to his bookkeepers, and that 95 percent of all the
companies' deductions were legitimate. On Monday, in arguing for
dismissal of the charges, defense lawyer Robert Giuffra said the
prosecution found ''no effort to cover anything up.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors Cathy Seibel and Elliott Jacobson, who rested their
case Monday, would not comment on the defense strategy, nor would
Marvin Smilon, spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro said only, ''I feel great'' outside court. His lawyers
refused to say why they didn't call witnesses, though typically it
reflects confidence that the prosecution did not meet the burden of
proof.
</P>
<P>
   The defense said later, at a conference with the judge about how
to instruct the jury, that one witness they wanted to call -
Pirro's office manager, Marie Tedeschi - had refused, invoking her
right not to testify against herself. Defense lawyer Annemarie
Hassett said the prosecution had rendered Tedeschi ''unavailable''
by refusing to grant her immunity after telling her she might be
prosecuted. The judge said that was not improper.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, who attended much of the trial
and was mentioned in court every day, said, ''It's clear there was
no need'' to present witnesses on her husband's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ''I agree with the defense decision,'' she said. ''I understand
it and I think the jury will as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge scheduled closing arguments for Wednesday and Thursday
and said jury deliberations would begin Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1828 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divers, dogs search unsuccessfully for boat crash victims  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) - Divers and cadaver-sniffing dogs
searched unsuccessfully again Tuesday for two people missing and
presumed dead in a boating accident that killed two others.
</P>
<P>
   While the grieving mother of Jean Greenwood, 30, of Sewell,
watched from shore, four State Police boats dragged the bottom of
Peck's Bay for more than six hours, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like a needle in a haystack out there,'' said Sgt. Steve
Cozzi, head of the underwater recovery unit.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood and James G. Fisler, 25, of Sewell, were among four
occupants of a 26-food speedboat that was broadsided by a cabin
cruiser about 7 p.m. Sunday. They were knocked overboard and
haven't been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   Two other men in the boat, including driver Dominic Laspata, 26,
of Westville, were killed. State Police confirmed Tuesday that
Greenwood was aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The nine people aboard the 30-foot cabin cruiser, here to attend
a North Penn High School graduation party at the home of a
classmate, escaped serious injury, including driver John Lego, 52,
of Lansdale, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   James Swiggard, 18, of Norristown, Pa., who was listed in
serious condition Monday at Atlantic City Medical Center, was
transferred to another hospital Tuesday. No further information was
available; the family asked that no information be released,
Atlantic City Medical Center spokeswoman Debbie Wrigley said.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, authorities and family members alike had given up
hope that either of the missing people would be found alive.
</P>
<P>
   State Police divers, assisted by Palisades Search &AMP; Rescue Dog
Association dogs, searched an area 300 yards wide by a half-mile
long, dragging the bay bottom with hooks.
</P>
<P>
   A State Police helicopter hovered about 100 feet above them for
part of the afternoon, with troopers looking down at the shallow
water shoals surrounding salt marsh flats in search of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   They were hampered by high wind, choppy water and the fact that
the exact point where the collision occurred was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ''The point of impact is easy to determine in a road accident,
because you have skid marks,'' said Cozzi. ''I don't have a point
of impact here. If I had one, we'd be better off.''
</P>
<P>
   The water in the search area ranges from three to 15 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   The southbound cabin cruiser and the northbound speedboat, which
were traveling in an area outside a ''no wake'' zone with no speed
limit, both turned east just before the collision.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin cruiser plowed into the left side of the speedboat,
sending all nine occupants of the cruiser flying into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no clue what was going on,'' said Kenneth Myers Jr., 18,
of Lansdale, one of the survivors. ''I thought someone had pushed
me off the boat to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers landed in the water next to one of the dead men.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a bunch of debris all over the place. I found a body
and brought it on to the other boat. He had lacerations across the
face. His face was not recognizable at all,'' Myers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, who suffered an elbow injury, a groin injury and a blow
to the head, was treated and released from a hospital Sunday. On
Tuesday, he was to get a complete mental and physical evaluation,
his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's all right, not great,'' said Kathy Myers, 50. ''He keeps
talking about how the guy looked.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody, a cadaver-sniffing border collie who wore an orange life
jacket, responded to scents in five different locations Tuesday but
each time, divers found no body, Cozzi said.
</P>
<P>
   The divers and dogs quit about 4 p.m. Tuesday but State Police
skiffs were to continue searching the water's surface through the
night. The full-scale search will resume Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood's mother, Ruth Greenwood, sat on the back bumper of a
State Police truck with four unidentified friends as the search
continued Tuesday, occasionally embracing them.
</P>
<P>
   When one of the State Police boats came in, the five rushed to
the dock to ask Trooper David Burns for a progress report.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Fisler's former wrestling coach at Gloucester County
College, Chuck Williamson, stood with his wife, peering through
binoculars at the recovery operation about 300 yards from shore.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, 58, of Woodbury, called him ''a good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He wasn't an all-American and he wasn't the best on the team,
but whenever we needed him, he was there. This is heartbreaking,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Glassboro Police Department, where Fisler worked as a
part-time police officer, the mood was somber.
</P>
<P>
   ''You always pray that he still might be safe somewhere, but
that certainly does not seem too promising right now,'' said Police
Chief Patricia Kunchynski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
