<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept Supports Texas SBC Bid  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department lent its support
Tuesday to a bid by SBC Communications to offer long-distance
telephone service to its local customers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing itself, the department recommended that the Federal
Communications Commission permit SBC to enter the long-distance
market within its region. The commission, which must take into
account the Justice Department's evaluation, has until July 3 to
render a decision.
</P>
<P>
   If SBC gains approval to offer long-distance service, it would
mark only the second time that a local Bell company has met the
standards set forth by a 1996 telecommunications law. This
checklist requires that a Bell company must show in detail that it
has opened its local monopoly to give rivals a chance to compete,
before being allowed to offer long-distance service in those
markets. So far, Bell Atlantic has been the only company to meet
the test, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   SBC filed its initial application to offer long-distance service
in Texas at the beginning of this year. The bid received harsh
reviews from the Justice Department, which said the company had not
done enough to give competing companies access to its network, as
required by law, and recommended that the FCC deny the petition.
</P>
<P>
   The company ultimately requested a new review to bolster its
application with more information.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Justice Department said the company had provided
data indicating significant improvement on a number of matters.
Those include SBC's handling of requests from rival businesses
seeking to lease lines so they could offer high-speed Internet
service and its processing of orders to switch local phone
customers to competing providers.
</P>
<P>
   The department added, however, that ''additional performance
measures and ongoing refinement of performance measurement
processes are likely to be needed as new services and technologies
are implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also must determine whether the new data accurately
reflect SBC's performance, the department said in its filing.
</P>
<P>
   It said the commission also should ensure ''that adequate
mechanisms exist to resolve emerging issues that will affect
competition.'' Those include a complaint by rival companies that
SBC is not allowing them to share certain lines to deliver
high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   The department noted that those issues already are before the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's support will join two endorsements from
the Texas Public Utility Commission, which the FCC also must
consider.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll give the DOJ's recommendation careful consideration
along with that of the state of Texas and our own public record,''
said an FCC spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   SBC welcomed the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The department's ''filing represents an impartial and objective
determination that the local market in Texas is irreversibly open
and that robust competition exists in that market,'' said Priscilla
Hill-Ardoin, senior vice president for Federal Regulatory Affairs
for SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   She said this marked the first time the department has given its
full support to an application by a Bell company seeking to offer
local customers long-distance service. Bell Atlantic did not
receive a full-force endorsement for New York service from the
Justice Department, but the FCC ultimately gave its approval in
late December.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: SBC: http://www.sbc.com/
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department: http://www.usdoj.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission: http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
