<HEADLINE> Lazio: I'll need $15 million or more for Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio says he will need ''a ton of
dough'' - at least $15 million - to run his Senate campaign against
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Tuesday on Don Imus' nationally syndicated morning
talk show, the little-known congressman from Long Island said,
''We're going to need a lot of money. ... It's a ton of dough.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton visited a hospital in suburban Westchester
County where she continued to attack the Republican as someone hard
to pin down on issues. She cited his support Monday for hate crimes
legislation approved last week by the GOP-led state Senate. Gay
rights groups in the past have been highly critical of Lazio for
not being supportive of such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to have a great time trying to figure out where
he stands on issues,'' the first lady said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Imus show, Lazio said, ''We're going to need $15 million
or more'' for the race against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Through March 31, Clinton had raised more than $12 million for
the Senate race while her Republican opponent at the time, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, had collected more than $19 million. On May 19,
the New York City mayor withdrew from the race to deal with his
prostate cancer and Lazio announced his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   When Lazio suspended his Senate campaign plans last year at Gov.
George Pataki's request to allow Giuliani a clear run at Clinton,
the congressman had about $3.5 million in his campaign bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the first lady have said they plan to raise $25 million
for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said his fund raising was going well, although the only
detail he provided was that his Internet campaign site had
generated about $300,000 in contributions since he entered the
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   There was no response from the Lazio campaign Tuesday about how
much money in all the candidate has raised since Giuliani's May 19
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's comments came as a fourth statewide poll since Lazio got
into the race showed the Senate race to be a close one. The New
York Times/CBS News poll had Clinton favored by 44 percent of
voters to 39 percent for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 1,187 likely voters was conducted June
4-10 and has a margin of error of plus of minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The three polls out earlier either showed the race very close or
a statistical dead heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
