<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-conviction DNA testing bill unveiled by Hatch  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - New York Attorney General Elliot Spitzer urged
the Senate Judiciary Committee to adopt a national standard to
provide those already convicted of crimes with access to DNA
testing that could establish their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Such a standard is already in place in New York and has not been
as costly or burdensome as critics had predicted, Spitzer said at a
Capitol Hill hearing Tuesday. He said DNA evidence has led to at
least seven exonerations in New York, which is one of only a few
states that has such a post-conviction standard in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our experience demonstrates that post-conviction DNA testing
can bolster the integrity of our judicial system without unduly
burdening our criminal justice system,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, unveiled a more restrictive bill than New York's.
Another bipartisan bill being pushed by Sens. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.,
and Gordon Smith, R-Ore., is broader. It includes federal
competency requirements for defense lawyers in capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where more executions take place then any other state,
the lack of quality defense counsel in capital cases has become a
''crisis,'' according to former Texas Court of Criminal Appeals
Judge Charles Baird.
</P>
<P>
   ''And I can guarantee you that the state of Texas is not going
to address that,'' said Baird, who is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's bill gives momentum to post-conviction genetic testing
as debate rages over capital punishment. Several men were released
from death row in Illinois in recent months, some because DNA
evidence cleared them. That prompted Illinois Gov. George Ryan to
place a temporary moratorium on executions there.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Barry Scheck, founder of the New York
City-based Innocence Project, and former death row inmate Dennis
Fritz, of Kansas City, Mo., were among those on Capitol Hill
testifying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is an urgent need for national legislation to assist a
narrow but important group of people: those who are sentenced to
decades in prison, or sit on death row, but could show through
post-conviction testing that they were wrongly imprisoned or
sentenced,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Tuesday's hearing focused on what the threshold should
be for DNA testing post-conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy's bill would provide for DNA testing in cases where the
evidence is relevant to the defendant's claim that he or she is
wrongfully convicted or sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's bill is more narrow. It allows for DNA testing only if
the perpetrator's identity was an issue at the trial and if the
results could establish the defendant's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a request for DNA testing is only granted if there
is a reasonable probability that if the results were admitted at
trial the verdict wold have been more favorable to the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the hearing, Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said he was
introducing a bill to eliminate the backlog of DNA kits that have
yet to be tested. Schumer would spend $100 million over four years
to test the backlog of 180,000 DNA kits. In New York, there is a
backlog of 15,000 rape kits sitting in a refrigerated warehouse
waiting to be testing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar bills are pending in the House sponsored by New York
Reps. Benjamin Gilman, a Republican, and Anthony Weiner, a
Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1857 </TRAILER>
