<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Party Revives Old Tactics  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON
The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- As a tight presidential election draws near,
activist groups charge that the government is falling back on old
practices -- using patronage and pressure on public employees to get
out the vote for the party that has run Mexico for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   The government denies such claims. After repeated electoral
reforms, officials pledge the July 2 vote will be clean, with no
ballot-stuffing or stealing and an independent agency to do the
counting.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, several observer groups presented what they said
was evidence that the ruling party has dusted off some of its old
techniques of staying in power.
</P>
<P>
   Impoverished families in several parts of the country have been
told their children's $40-per-month government scholarships will
stop unless they sign a list promising to vote for ruling-party
candidates, one observer group said.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of such lists -- emblazoned with the emblem of
ruling-party presidential candidate Francisco Labastida and bearing
the addresses and voter I.D. numbers of potential voters -- were
among the documents made public Tuesday by Alianza Civica, a
nonpartisan group that campaigns for fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   In two states, opposition parties say, they have found
warehouses where the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party is
piling up pre-election gifts like bicycles, sewing machines and
sacks of cement. Alianza Civica also distributed copies of a letter
allegedly written by an official in the southern state of Chiapas
ordering government employees to attend ruling-party campaign
rallies and paying for the bus to get them there.
</P>
<P>
   But the official, Francisco Cueto, denied having written the
letters. He called them ''a fake'' and said the government-paid bus
transported only ''fishermen, athletes, social groups we try to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI officials did not immediately return phone calls seeking
comment about the voter lists.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations come as the ruling party, known by the acronym
PRI, is facing one of the toughest challenges to its 71 years in
power. Labastida is in a statistical dead heat with Vicente Fox of
the conservative National Action Party, according to most recent
polls.
</P>
<P>
   PRI denies it is violating rules. It has forbidden the use of
government funds for campaigns, and it says voters are too smart to
be bought by pressure or promises.
</P>
<P>
   ''People aren't stupid,'' said Social Development Secretary
Carlos Jarque. Jarque said his agency has received less than a
half-dozen complaints of political use of government funds and has
yet to find any evidence to support them.
</P>
<P>
   The official Federal Electoral Institute, the independent
watchdog agency, says it has received 12 complaints of vote-buying
or pressure tactics, 10 against the PRI and two against opposition
parties.
</P>
<P>
   But activists are preparing to submit dozens more complaints.
And the PRI has many faces -- front groups such as the Territorial
Movement, which helps implement rural public works projects and
then passes credit for them on to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people don't know where our movement ends and the PRI
begins,'' said Wintilo Vega, a leader of the Territorial Movement.
''We are the new face of the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say recent changes in Mexico's anti-poverty programs
made them more likely to be used as campaign fodder. The former
Solidarity program -- a pork-barrel operation that handed out aid to
communities -- has been replaced in part by individual-aid programs
under President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of the these programs are directed toward individuals,
which makes them more potentially subject to manipulation,'' said
Meyer Brownstone, one of the Canadian observers.
</P>
<P>
   And as hard as it is to detect illegal electoral tactics, it's
even harder to punish them, despite sweeping reforms in electoral
law. The Federal Electoral Institute says it needs more money to
investigate the cases, stiffer enforcement practices and clearer
laws on what's acceptable politicking and what's not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No civil rights charges in police killing of black man  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A federal investigation has found no
basis for civil rights charges against the white policemen who
killed a young black man in Ossining two years ago, the U.S.
attorney announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The killing brought to a boil the simmering antagonism between
some blacks and the police in Ossining, a village of 22,000 best
known for the maximum-security Sing Sing prison.
</P>
<P>
   The federal decision is consistent with the finding of a
Westchester grand jury, which voted not to indict officers Raymond
DeBenedictus, Richard Damiano and Daniel Slater, all of whom are
still on the Ossining force.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Malone, 24, was shot and killed on James Street in
the predawn hours of July 19, 1998, after police were told that he
had fired a gun nearby. When police arrived, saw Malone and
directed him to stop, he ran away and the officers chased him, the
grand jury found.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Malone turned toward the officers and pointed a
.40-caliber handgun at them. Police fired and killed him.
</P>
<P>
   That night, about 200 angry people gathered outside police
headquarters, expressing doubts about police motives at a hastily
called meeting of the Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Brooks, a former head of Ossining's NAACP chapter, called
the killing ''an execution.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a policeman's dream, shooting a black man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's mother, Renee, expressed outrage at reports her son had
been shot five to 10 times, but urged witnesses to cooperate with
the investigation. Authorities never publicly disclosed how many
times Malone was shot.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said the federal investigation
failed to establish beyond a reasonable doubt that the officers
specifically intended to use unreasonable force.
</P>
<P>
   Village attorney Thomas Barnes said, ''We're pleased with the
finding and it conforms to our own analysis of the facts of the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that a civil case is pending - Mrs. Malone has sued the
village and the officers for $20 million - he said the federal
finding ''can't hurt the village.''
</P>
<P>
   Regina Darby, lawyer for the mother, said, ''This is not the
first time that a DA's office or the federal government have failed
to seriously examine and become involved in police activities.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro said, ''The Malone family bears
a terrible loss here, but we believe that the finding is consistent
with the finding of the Westchester grand jury two years ago. ...
The police officers in this case acted in a manner that was
consistent with the law and we hope this can bring closure to all
involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
