<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Seeks Action in Congo  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
recommended Tuesday that the Security Council demand the immediate
withdrawal of Ugandan and Rwandan troops from Congo and impose
sanctions if they refuse to go.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said they expect the council to approve a
resolution this week demanding such a pullout. The comments came
after days of fighting between Rwanda and Uganda in the northern
Congolese town of Kisangani that left an estimated 150 civilians
dead, more than 1,000 injured and extensive property damage.
</P>
<P>
   Annan asked the council to act under Chapter 7 of the U.N.
Charter, which allows for a variety of escalating measures -- from
diplomatic and economic sanctions to military enforcement as a
final option. The secretary-general has sanctions in mind as an
option if Rwanda and Uganda reject the council's call, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also urged the council to demand the subsequent withdrawal
of all other foreign forces in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda, Uganda and other neighboring nations have been in Congo
taking sides in the central African nation's 22-month-old civil
war. Congo President Laurent Kabila has received support from
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe. Rwanda and Uganda, meanwhile, took
the side of rival rebel groups, which should have made them allies
against Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rwanda-Uganda alliance fell apart, and the two sides
have clashed several times in Kisangani. Annan said troops from the
two countries must be held accountable for deaths, injuries and
destruction in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general's request for the council to act marked a
toughening of U.N. resolve to get all parties in Congo to implement
a cease-fire signed last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council has authorized a 5,537-strong U.N. force to
monitor the cease-fire, but deployment depends on security
guarantees. So far, the U.N. mission in Congo only has about 200
unarmed military observers and liaison officers.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said none of the conditions to start deploying the force
in July as planned have been met: The parties are not adhering to
the cease-fire or cooperating with U.N. personnel, U.N. staff
members don't have freedom of movement and troops being offered to
the U.N. mission don't have adequate strength, equipment and
training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
