<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts of new club drug Ecstasy  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Facts about the so-called club drug Ecstasy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drug: Ecstasy
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacological Name: 3-4 Methylene-dioxy-Methamphetamine,
abbreviated as MDMA.
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Ecstacy, X, XTC, Adam, Essence, M&AMP;M, Love Drug.
</P>
<P>
   Dose: Usually taken orally as a small pill, 75 mg. to 300 mg.,
typically the size of children's aspirin, commonly yellow but known
to occur in variety of colors, often with a counterfeit commercial
logo (Nike, Playboy, Mitsubishi) imprinted on the pill.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacological Effect: Impact 40 to 60 minutes after ingestion,
produces effect for four to six hours by overexciting the brain
neurons that produce serotonin, a neurotransmitter chemical used to
regulate emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Origin: Emerged in 1910s as appetite suppressant.
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate Use: Limited use in psychotherapy in 1970s, 1980s to
help patients reveal pent-up emotions, no longer classified for
medical use in United States.
</P>
<P>
   Illegitimate Use: Popular in underage club scene where alcohol
use would be illegal and difficult to conceal. Associated with
''rave'' concerts and dance events.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits: Some users claim a sense of well being and sensuality,
reduced anxiety and social inhibition, heightened sensory
perception and euphoric relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Detriments: Muscle tightness, including grinding and clenching
teeth, faintness, nausea, chills, sweats, severe dehydration,
elevated body temperature and blood pressure, sudden anxiety and
paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Dangers: Health studies find increased risk of extreme
dehydration or dangerous elevation of body temperature, prolonged
use linked to damage of neurons that produce serotonin, which can
cause permanent disability to emotional and memory functions of the
brain.
Source: National Institute On Drug Abuse, Tennessee Department of
Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
