<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate says it is in stretch run of 2000 session  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - People who abandon newborns in hospitals or
other settings where the safety of the babies is not imperiled
would not face prosecution under a bill unanimously passed Tuesday
in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was one of scores of bills approved as the Senate
held what its leader said was its next-to-last meeting of the 2000
session.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's passage of legislation also quickened after weeks
of leisurely activity as members of that house hoped to get the
bills they favored over to the Senate in time for consideration by
that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann, a Republican from Onondaga County,
said the abandoned baby bill will save lives. New mothers who
because of their age or distraught mental state are inclined to
abandon babies in trash bins might get newborns into safe hands if
they knew they would not be prosecuted as criminals, Hoffmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The message the bill would convey to such parents is, ''We will
welcome you and we will not ask questions if you need that
anonymity. We will not ask questions if you deliver that infant
safely up to three days old,'' Hoffmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John DeFrancisco, R-Syracuse, voted for the bill but said
it does not define thoroughly enough what an ''appropriate''
setting is for a baby to be left in so a parent can avoid
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrancisco said the measure appeared to him to be at ''great
risk'' of being declared unconstitutionally vague by courts.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann said she believes the abandoned baby bill will be
approved by both the Democrat-controlled state Assembly and Gov.
George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally Tuesday, a newborn was surrendered at Seton
Health-St. Mary's Hospital in Troy under ''Project Safe Haven.'' It
is a program entered into by prosecutors and other authorities in
nine Albany-area counties including Rensselaer County District
Attorney Kenneth Bruno. He is son of the Senate's Republican leader
Joseph Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   As has become his habit, Joseph Bruno said he would stick to a
self-imposed deadline for the ''completion'' of his chamber's
regular session. Six months ago, he set this Wednesday, June 14, as
the last day of the Senate's meeting this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's insistence on adhering to such deadlines is designed to
compel the Assembly and the governor to make final deals on issues
under negotiation or face the prospect of the Senate leaving town
without passing those agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said the Legislature has been in session for 5{ months
this year and ''we shouldn't be now in a mad, mad rush.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yet I think if we were here another month, we would be in the
same mode,'' Bruno told radio station WROW-AM in Albany Tuesday.
''Unfortunately, the Legislature seems to need a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said talks over some major issues facing lawmakers have
''lagged.''
</P>
<P>
   If past years have been any guide, the Senate will come back
into session for a day or two later in the year to ratify deals
made with the Assembly and governor after senators break for the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, Bruno and state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver all said
Tuesday they had long ''wish'' lists of bills they want to see
passed before the legislative session ends.
</P>
<P>
   ''My to-do list is so long that if the Legislature started
passing bills today I don't think that it could be done three days
from now,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major issues outstanding Tuesday were agreements over
a bill to toughen penalties for crimes committed by bigoted
offenders, to impose more controls over the sale of guns, to
toughen penalties for sex assaults and school violence, to expand
DNA testing of criminals and to give automatic cost-of-living
increases to state and local government retirees.
</P>
<P>
   In other legislative actions Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   -The Senate approved a bill expanding from $100,000 to $150,000
the size of the maximum raffle award which can be offered by
nonprofit groups in New York.
</P>
<P>
   -The Assembly passed a bill to give people falsely accused of
abusing a child a way to appeal to the state to get their names
removed from the state's sex abuse registry. Currently, people's
names remain on the registry for 10 years, even if the accusations
against them are found to be baseless.
</P>
<P>
   -The Assembly gave final legislative approval to a bill allowing
the victims of slave labor camps run by Nazi Germany or their heirs
to recover damages in court. The measure would waive the state's
statute of limitations for filing suits for the World War II-era
human rights abuses in labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   -Youth sports coaches would have to undergo background checks
designed to weed out sex offenders and child abusers under a
measure passed by the Senate and sent to the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   -The Assembly passed another bill requiring the sale of
''fire-safe'' cigarettes in New York. It would replace the one
vetoed last month by Pataki and is written to address some of the
governor's objections to the first bill. The measure would give
tobacco companies six more months to comply with the law, to
October 2002, and also prohibit the marketing of any
self-extinguishing cigarettes which are more dangerous than he
conventional cigarettes currently on the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1922 </TRAILER>
