<HEADLINE> State Senate passes casino gambling bill  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Senate Tuesday unanimously passed
a bill requiring legislative and local approval before Indian
tribes can open gambling casinos on non-tribal lands.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would apply to construction of new casinos on
off-reservation lands once they are approved by the federal
government. It would also prevent the state's governor to exert
executive authority over casino construction.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation would assure that there is sufficient state
and local input into any gaming contracts for a casino on
non-tribal lands,'' Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Padavan, a Queens Republican, voted in favor of the
bill but said he favored a broader application to include both on-
and off-reservation lands.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill goes only so far. It should go all the way,''
Padavan said. ''Whether the casino is located on (tribal) property
or away, there's absolutely no difference in terms of the
socio-economic impact to the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation is similar to a measure proposed by Gov.
George Pataki in March, but it does not include legalizing
traditional slot machines in the casinos - a key provision in
Pataki's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said Tuesday that he's ''concerned'' that slot machines
was not included in the bill. Pataki has said that it's not clear
whether a ban on slots in the state constitution applies to Indian
casinos. He said that his version would have cleared up those
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that it's very important if we're going to have
successful casinos ... that would be able to compete with casinos
from other surrounding jurisdictions,'' Pataki said. ''I'm
disappointed it's not in the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he would support a bill that excluded slot
machines, Pataki answered: ''I have reservations without that
language in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would still need approval from the Assembly before it
goes to the Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Carrier, a spokesman for Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver, said the chamber has a bill matching the Senate's version,
''but we have not made a decision yet on what we're going to do
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver had previously supported bills that would have limited
casinos to traditional tourism areas such as Sullivan and Ulster
counties in the Catskills and Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Regis Mohawk Nation has received federal approval to
build a casino on the Monticello Raceway in Sullivan County, about
90 miles northwest of New York City. But it was still uncertain
what would become of that deal after tribal leaders signed a
separate agreement with Park Place Entertainment, the world's
largest gambling company, to build a casino at a Catskill resort
separate from the raceway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 1926 </TRAILER>
