<HEADLINE> Paraguayan Fugitive Seeks Transfer  </HEADLINE>
By STAN LEHMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- The attorney for a former Paraguayan
army chief facing murder charges called for his client to be moved
to a military post Tuesday, saying police can't protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gen. Gen. Lino Oviedo was arrested in Brazil Sunday in
connection with the 1999 killing of his nation's vice president. He
is being held in a federal police jail in Brazil's capital, where
he was awaiting a ruling on his extradition to Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a price on my client's head,'' attorney Inemar Penna
Marinho said by phone. ''And the facilities at the federal police
are just not secure enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinho said he will ask the Supreme Court to order the
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ''His opponents in Paraguay have offered to pay $1 million if he
is bought back alive and $2 million if he is returned dead,''
Marinho said. ''An army barracks would provide more safety and the
comfort a prisoner of his status deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   A former presidential candidate, Oviedo is accused of plotting
the killing of Vice President Luis Argana. He was also convicted of
leading an unsuccessful coup in 1996, and was suspected of planning
another on May 18 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo was flown to Brasilia on Monday, following his arrest in
Foz do Iguacu -- a tourist resort on the southwest border with
Paraguay and Argentina. Brazilian police had been searching for him
since May 26, when the Supreme Court issued a warrant at Paraguay's
request.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay has 90 days to formally request Oviedo's extradition,
or the general goes free, Supreme Court spokesman Gerson Matos
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Paraguayan government may take several days to file the
request, said Paraguay Embassy official Jorge Figueredo. ''We must
be sure that the request details all the charges against Oviedo.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing arguments from both sides, the federal attorney
general will give an opinion on the extradition, and the Supreme
Court will make the decision.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Oviedo is sharing a cell with two Brazilians
drug traffickers and a German awaiting extradition on charges of
attempted homicide, federal police chief Romulo Berredo said. The
two-story concrete prison building was housing about 40 inmates,
mostly on drug-trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''So far he has proven to be a model prisoner,'' Berredo said.
''He is extremely polite.''
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo was sentenced once in Paraguay to a 10-year prison term
for the 1996 coup attempt, but was released after only six months
by then-President Raul Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   He went into exile in Argentina, but vanished on Dec. 9, a day
before the country's new president, Fernando de la Rua, took
office. De la Rua had said he would consider Paraguay's request for
extradition, which his predecessor had rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayan authorities said intelligence agents traced his phone
calls to Foz do Iguacu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1929 </TRAILER>
