<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey's jobless rate edges up slightly in April  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey's jobless rate held steady in
May at 3.8 percent, unchanged from April, according to labor
statistics released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's unemployment rate has hovered around or below the
U.S. rate, which was 4.1 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey posted job gains totaling 10,000 from April to May,
according to state labor officials.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the job growth came from federal jobs related to the
census, officials said. The public sector added a total of 8,400
jobs in New Jersey over the month, a growth fueled primarily by
temporary census-taking positions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only job growth in the nation was all census-related,''
said Kevin Smith, state labor department spokesman. ''Nationally,
private sector jobs actually dropped in May. In New Jersey, we had
a slight increase in private sector jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The private sector added 1,600 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest private sector increase was in the service area,
which posted 2,600 new jobs. Research and development, testing
laboratories and management and public relations led the growth in
this area.
</P>
<P>
   Construction jobs were also up by 900. This was the fastest pace
of growth since 4,300 construction jobs were added in the first
five months of 1994, labor officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing industry lost 600 jobs. Jobholding in
transportation/communications/public utilities also dropped by
1,100 over the month. The decrease was mostly in the communications
sector.
</P>
<P>
   April was the 32nd straight month that the state's unemployment
rate remained under 5 percent, labor officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1994, New Jersey employers have added 423,600
jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
