<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Attacker Arrives in Turkey  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy on Tuesday pardoned the Turkish gunman who
tried to kill Pope John Paul II in 1981, and he was immediately
delivered to authorities in Turkey -- taking with him the answers to
the mysterious assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pardon, Mehmet Ali Agca must now serve time in
Turkey for a killing that took place before the attack on the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Agca, white-haired after nearly two decades in jail, left the
Italian prison where he had been held after dark Tuesday, under
heavy guard and carrying nothing but an armful of books.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at Istanbul's Ataturk International Airport early
Wednesday. Police backed by armored personnel carriers blocked off
the gate where he landed, CNN-Turk reported.
</P>
<P>
   In his last hours in Italy, Agca offered profuse thanks to the
pope, who had personally forgiven and comforted his would-be killer
during a 1983 visit to Agca's prison cell. The Vatican in recent
days had reassured the government that John Paul supported the act
of clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ''That the granting of pardon comes during Holy Year
celebrations makes the pope's personal satisfaction even more
intense,'' papal spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said.
</P>
<P>
   On May 13, 1981, Agca pulled a trigger twice as John Paul rode
smiling and waving in an open car through excited throngs of
pilgrims in St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   One shot hit the pope's abdomen, barely missing vital organs.
Doctors say the wound forever weakened the pope, then an athletic
hiker and skier, now a frail, stooped 80-year-old suffering from
symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The former Soviet bloc was immediately suspected in the attack --
suspicions that lingered over the years despite denials by former
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and the one-time spy chief for
the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet spy chiefs were seen as fearing the adamantly
anti-communist pope would spur popular revolts against the Soviet
bloc -- as John Paul in fact did, above all in his native Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Agca had told investigators he acted at the instigation of the
Bulgarian secret service and the Soviet KGB. But Italian courts
ruled there was insufficient evidence to support the accusations,
and Agca himself went on to give widely varying accounts during his
19 years and one month behind bars in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Agca purposefully feigned insanity in court to cast doubt on the
credibility of his own stories, a prosecutor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This extinguishes the last hope of reaching the truth,''
prosecutor Antonio Marini said of the pardon and extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Rosario Priore, who investigated the alleged
conspiracy between Bulgarian agents and Agca, agreed that the truth
has never emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Priore insisted, the pardon was the correct move.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the only possible act to take,'' Priore said. ''You can't
keep people in prison just to make them talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Agca, now 42, smiled in relief when Tuesday's news reached his
prison at Ancona, in eastern Italy, lawyer Marina Magistrelli said.
</P>
<P>
   '''It's a dream,''' Magistrelli quoted Agca as exclaiming,
saying he offered thanks to the pope, the Vatican and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul credits the Virgin Mary for sparing his life. The
Vatican said in May that the assassination attempt had been
foretold in a vision seen by three peasant children in Fatima,
Portugal, in 1917 -- the so-called third secret of Fatima.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the shooting, cameras filmed the white-robed
pontiff visiting a clearly grateful Agca in prison. The heads of
gunman and victim alike were bowed in an intense conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Agca carried out the attack after escaping from prison in
Turkey, where he was being held in the killing of a Turkish
newspaper editor. Turkey later convicted him in absentia in the
killing and sentenced him to death. A 1991 amnesty reduced the
sentence to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After expiration of that sentence -- minus 158 days served before
his escape -- Turkey will put Agca on trial for a 1979 robbery in
Istanbul, Turkish Justice Minister Hikmet Sami Turk said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to go to Turkey, pay his debt there like he did in
Italy and walk out a free man,'' said Magistrelli, Agca's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll be 50,'' she said. ''That's a whole life spent in
prison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 1943 </TRAILER>
