<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man admits his ring stole checks from Bank of New York 'lock boxes' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - An Essex County man admitted Tuesday that he
was part of a ring that stole checks being processed by the Bank of
New York in Newark and altered the checks to negotiate them.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money stolen during the nearly four-year operation
was not immediately disclosed by federal prosecutors and the FBI,
who are continuing to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The amount could be substantial, based on one specific incident
cited by Justin Jades as he pleaded guilty: in March 1999, he
arranged to buy $224,800 worth of computer parts and electrical
equipment using stolen checks deposited directly into the accounts
of the seller.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his plea bargain, Jades has agreed to cooperate with
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   He said the checks were stolen from Bank of New York ''lock
boxes,'' then altered, and deposited either into accounts he and
others opened under false names, or into the accounts of companies
from which they purchased merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lock boxes'' are not objects that hold checks, it is a term
for a service provided by bankers to business customers who want
incoming checks processed so the money can be deposited quickly
into interest-bearing instruments.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this service, the bank receives checks directly from
those who send the company money, deposits the funds, and informs
the company of who has paid.
</P>
<P>
   Jades, 34, who lived in East Orange before his arrest in August,
pleaded guilty to a single charge of conspiracy to commit bank
fraud. He remains in federal custody at the Union County Jail in
Elizabeth, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Lorraine S. Gerson, who is
prosecuting the case.
</P>
<P>
   He faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine when
sentenced Sept. 7 by U.S. District Judge William H. Walls, although
the actual penalties would be far less.
</P>
<P>
   The plot began about November 1995. In May 1996, Jades rented
office space in Fords, Middlesex County, to establish an address
for new accounts, which he and at least two unnamed others opened
at the Fleet Bank in Concord, N.H., he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jades also obtained a driver's license and birth certificate in
the fictitious name of ''Jim Weda'' to open a bank account, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
