<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden school board president urges nationwide search for superintendent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - After more than a year without a permanent
school superintendent, the Board of Education president is urging
the board to renew a nationwide search.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that it's time for us to move on,'' President Philip
E. Freeman Sr. told fellow board members at a meeting Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Roy J. Dawson took early retirement last June. In
April 1999, the school board hired Leonard Fitts, a former
consultant to the district who was superintendent in nearby Penns
Grove and dean of students at Cheyney State University in
Pennsylvania, as interim superintendent. He will leave the post
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Freeman, business manager and school board secretary, said
Tuesday that Fitts, receiving $500 per day, was paid about $133,000
from April 1999 through April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members support the appointment of Josiha Haig as
superintendent and opposed Philip Freeman's suggestion to create
another search committee.
</P>
<P>
   Haig was superintendent in Hartford, Conn., and East Orange. His
nomination was voted down twice after board members learned he had
not served long enough as a principal to satisfy the board's
requirements. Philip Freeman said appointing Haig could cause legal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Dwaine Williams said he would introduce Haig's name
for consideration a third time.
</P>
<P>
   The board took no action on creating a search committee Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Freeman also asked the board to appoint a new interim
superintendent until a permanent one is hired.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the district, which is being monitored by the
state, needs to act quickly. He compared it to a sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   ''This system right now is bow first. You're taking on water,''
Williams said. ''You're the Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Camden is the largest public school district in southern New
Jersey with about 20,000 students.
</P>
</TEXT>
