<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer-stricken umpire visits College World Series  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG ALDEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) - Joe Casalunovo's greatest wish was to umpire
a College World Series game. He can't do that, but the amateur
umpire battling terminal cancer is watching this year's series from
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Casalunovo, who was diagnosed five years ago with colorectal
cancer that has spread to his lungs and liver, is here as a result
of some sympathetic doctors in Philadelphia and Omaha. The American
Cancer Society and an NCAA umpiring official also helped coordinate
the trip so Casalunovo could at least see a game at Rosenblatt
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing that so many people would put out so much effort
for somebody they don't know,'' Casalunovo said before Tuesday's
game between Clemson and Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Casalunovo, of Laurel Heights, N.J., looks and feels healthy.
His black hair and mustache have grown back in the sixth months
since his latest round of chemotherapy and he had no problems
strolling about the ballpark, shaking hands and posing for pictures
with the umpiring crew before Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ''My reports aren't that good, but I feel and look good,'' he
said. ''I have more energy than I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Casalunovo's dream of calling a game at Rosenblatt started when
he began watching the College World Series every June and noticed
the emotion the players showed for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''They may make some big bucks down the road, but right now
they're just playing because they love it. They want to be the
best,'' he said. ''That's what the College World Series is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Even through his chemotherapy, Casalunovo continued to call high
school and Division III college baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   He recently mentioned his umpiring during a conversation with
his oncologist, Dr. Bruce Boman, director of medical oncology and
medical genetics at Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia.
Casalunovo told Bowman how he enjoys watching the College World
Series each June and how much he would like to umpire a game there.
</P>
<P>
   Boman, the former director of the cancer center at Creighton
University, is a big CWS fan himself and still has some connections
back in Omaha. He called Dr. Alan Thorson, who he served with on
the Heartland Division of the American Cancer Society during their
days in Omaha. The two got to work on getting Casalunovo to Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   They coordinated flights for Casalunovo and his wife, Lorraine.
NCAA national coordinator of umpires Dave Yeast, who lost his
mother to breast cancer, set up the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ''They got him out here and we'll take him in and show him all
the sites of Omaha,'' Yeast said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeast gave Casalunovo a College World Series tote back and an
NCAA hat before Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ''This probably wouldn't have fit me six months ago when I
didn't have any hair,'' Casalunovo said.
</P>
<P>
   Casalunovo started following baseball while growing up in South
Philadelphia, going to Phillies games at Connie Mack Stadium and
later The Vet. He kept up with the game as an adult, but did not
get involved in umpiring until 12 years ago when his children were
playing baseball and softball.
</P>
<P>
   Casalunovo enjoyed the few games he called and, at the
suggestion of a neighbor, joined the umpires union. He is qualified
to do high school and small-college games and still gets behind the
plate when he is feeling up to it.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are days when you really do feel good but there is
nothing to do,'' he said. ''Now that I'm sitting around doing
nothing, it's not all it's cracked up to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The five years of treatment have not stopped the cancer from
spreading. Still, Casalunovo is not calling the trip a final wish.
He has remained optimistic throughout his illness and plans to
start a new protein treatment next month.
</P>
<P>
   Casalunovo wants people to be aware of colon cancer and not be
afraid to be checked for it. Casalunovo's uncle died of colon
cancer, but he didn't think much about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a topic everybody is comfortable talking about it,''
he said. ''If my family and I had talked about colon cancer I might
not be here today. I might be at home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 2023 </TRAILER>
