<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Former Bernardo Lawyer Ken Murray Acquitted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) -- Kenneth Murray's five years of
''hell on earth'' ended abruptly Tuesday as a judge acquitted the
former lawyer for sex killer Paul Bernardo of obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario Superior Court Justice Patrick Gravely said there was a
reasonable doubt Murray intended to impede the course of justice by
forever keeping Bernardo's gruesome sex-and-torture videotapes from
those trying convict him.
</P>
<P>
   Under Canada's Criminal Code, it must be proven an accused
willfully obstructed justice to be convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a dearth of similar cases, the Murray trial sets a
precedent for lawyers who are forced to deal with evidence that is
incriminating but also potentially helpful to their client's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gravely said it's possible, albeit hard to believe, that Murray
intended to use Bernardo's ''indescribably horrible'' videotapes to
defend his client.
</P>
<P>
   That casts doubt on the Crown's position that Murray -- who held
the tapes for more than 16 months after plucking them from
Bernardo's St. Catharines home in May 1993 -- planned to forever
keep them secret.
------
Amended Bank Law Strikes Balance Between Banks, Consumers: Martin
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Changes to financial service laws have balanced
the needs of consumers with the demands by Canada's banks and
insurance companies to be permitted to grow, Finance Minister Paul
Martin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the result is uneven, critics complained as Martin unveiled
the massive and long-awaited amendments to Canada's banking and
insurance rules.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition Canadian Alliance MPs complained the balance tipped
too far toward increasing the regulatory burden on banks.
</P>
<P>
   The NDP warned the legislation risks Canada's financial
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin maintained the bill -- with the heft of a big-city
telephone book -- was dynamic, flexible and fair.
------
Woman Killed on Highway Remembered As Mother, Top-Notch Police
Officer
</P>
<P>
   CHATHAM, Ontario (AP) -- To her fellow officers, Sgt. Marg Eve
was known as a top-notch police officer with extraordinary
compassion and expert negotiating skills.
</P>
<P>
   But the 38-year-old, who died last week after a gruesome
accident on Canada's busiest highway, was also celebrated Tuesday
as a strong woman with an infectious laugh whose greatest joy was
raising her two small children.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of police officers from across North America solemnly
filed into a small hockey arena to commemorate the life of Eve, who
died from massive head injuries at a London, Ontario, hospital
Friday, two days after a tractor-trailer hit three police cruisers
and another vehicle stopped on the side of Highway 401.
</P>
<P>
   She is the first female officer in Ontario to be killed while on
duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
