<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politics on TV: Lots of ads, little talk of issues  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Campaign commercials are overwhelming
broadcast news coverage of the presidential election, meaning
voters are getting more political spin than discussion of issues,
two studies conclude.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four months of the year, broadcasters in the top 75
media markets took in more than $114 million from more than 151,000
political ads, according to a report by the Alliance for Better
Campaigns, which advocates free television time for political
candidates. And by the time voters cast ballots on Nov. 7, TV
stations are expected to pocket some $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both network and local news shows included very
little substantive political coverage to balance the deluge of
advertising, according to a corollary report by the Norman Lear
Center at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University
of Southern California and the Annenberg Public Policy Center at
the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Stations only got credit for time spent with candidates
discussing issues, not reporting on strategy that dominates
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined 19 local TV stations in 11 cities and found:
</P>
<P>
   -The typical local TV station aired less than one minute of
candidates discussing issues each night. Sixteen of the stations
aired, on average, 39 seconds per night in the 30 days before a
primary.
</P>
<P>
   -Three stations involved in special election projects launched
by their owners offered much more coverage. WCVB in Boston averaged
4 minutes 19 seconds per night; WEWS in Cleveland averaged 3
minutes 49 seconds; and WMUR in Manchester, N.H., averaged 3
minutes 12 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Network news was even more paltry in its coverage, the Annenberg
study concluded. ABC, NBC and CBS aired a nightly average of just
36 seconds of candidates discussing issues, but spent more time
reporting on campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   For CBS, 77 percent of the stories were horse race coverage of
who's winning and who's losing. For NBC, it was 66 percent; for
ABC, 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the local level, the report used last week's New Jersey
Senate primary to dramatize its point.
</P>
<P>
   TV stations in New York and Philadelphia collected $21 million
from candidates, but top-rated stations serving the state featured
just 13 seconds per night of candidate discourse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 2105 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
