<DOCNO> APW20000613.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wagering board nominee defends her independent status  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki's nominee for the state
Racing and Wagering Board was confirmed by the Republican-led state
Senate Tuesday following a debate on the chamber's floor that ended
with a vote strictly along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Ritchko-Buley, the former chairwoman of the defunct
Freedom Party who was once enrolled as a Republican, said she will
''immerse myself in racing and wagering'' to make up for what she
lacks in experience.
</P>
<P>
   She was confirmed by the Senate 36-25, with all the Democrats
voting against Pataki's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Her nomination by the Republican governor came under scrutiny
when Democratic senators questioned her political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Martin Connor said Ritchko-Buley's
appointment will ''defy the spirit'' of the state law, which
prohibits all three members of the Racing and Wagering Board from
belonging to the same political party. The board's other two
members, Chairman Michael Hoblock and Joseph Neglia, are both
registered Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident that she's a faithful Republican,'' Connor, a
Brooklyn Democrat, said of Pataki's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchko-Buley, not enrolled in a political party, filed forms
Monday to retain that independent status and thus qualify for the
$101,600-a-year job. When her family moved to their Slingerlands
home last year, Ritchko-Buley said she enrolled as a Republican
after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, whom Ritchko-Buley worked
for in 1985-86, countered Connor's criticism and said, ''I don't
think it's appropriate to get personal and get political.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in the chamber just indicating that Mrs. Buley is an
intelligent, personable and very dignified lady,'' Bruno added.
''She has a background in dealing with very difficult issues ...
and is bright enough to learn everything she doesn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate on the Senate floor was an extension of what happened
at a meeting of the chamber's gaming, wagering and racing committee
earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yesterday it became apparent that she wouldn't meet the
requirement, so she changed her enrollment,'' Sen. Richard
Dollinger said in the meeting. ''The one qualification that this
nominee must have ... is that she can't be Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Dollinger, a Rochester Democrat, argued that Ritchko-Buley would
not have become an independent again ''unless you have a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ritchko-Buley became chairwoman of the Freedom Party, a
creation of the state Republican Party to add another party line
backing Pataki during his first run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchko-Buley's husband, Jeffrey Buley, is a lawyer for the
state Republican Chairman William Powers and has a lobbying
partnership with Albert Pirro. Pirro, a lobbyist and developer who
is married to Westchester County District Attorney Jeanine Pirro,
is being tried in federal court in White Plains for tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned by Dollinger what her political affiliation was
prior to joining the Freedom Party, Ritchko-Buley paused before
answering, ''I was enrolled as a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   But she insisted that she has been unenrolled after the Freedom
Party was disbanded in 1997 ''and I remained as such to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   After working for Bruno, Ritchko-Buley moved to public relations
firms in Albany and Boston. She said she had to essentially learn
about each client's issues in her public relations work, a skill
she intends to apply to her new job.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm fully confident of my ability to study and consider all
sides of the issue in a nonpartisan way,'' she said. ''I'd devote
myself to this new and exciting endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators on the committee urged members to focus on
Ritchko-Buley's qualifications and questioned if state laws were
violated when Ritchko-Buley's enrollment records were made public.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman William Larkin Jr., R-Orange, said that the
state Board of Election regulations prohibits enrollment records
from becoming public until after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin told Dollinger: ''If that box wasn't open to you, that
information would not be available.''
</P>
<P>
   Dollinger countered that he obtained the information from
Jeffrey Buley and added: ''If I were a blank, I would never go
there (Albany County Board of Elections) to reaffirm my
blankness.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats wanted the governor to reappoint Bennett Liebman, a
Democrat who has served two six-year terms on the board. Liebman's
term expired in February.
</P>
<P>
   Connor said Liebman is ''nationally recognized'' and by
confirming Ritchko-Buley, ''we're sending the wrong message to
people in the racing industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchko-Buley will be the first woman to serve on the
three-member board.
</P>
<P>
   The Wagering and Racing Board oversees all the state's legalized
gambling activities, including thoroughbred and harness horse
racing and off-track betting, except for the state Lottery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
