<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno To Seek Criminal Deportation  </HEADLINE>
By TONY FRASER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
said Tuesday she will seek agreements with other nations clarifying
U.S. policy on the deportation of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Reno signed such an agreement Monday with Trinidad. Speaking
here Tuesday during a meeting of law enforcement officials from the
Caribbean, Canada and Britain, Reno said she wanted an ''enhanced
partnership'' with more countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''My hope is that we can work together with everyone,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities' deportations of people from other countries
who commit crimes in the United States have been a sore point for
Caribbean countries, who complain they are being flooded with
U.S.-trained criminals. Because the inmates have not been charged
in their home countries, local police usually have to let them
loose -- even if they are violent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact signed by Reno and Trinidadian Prime Minister
Basdeo Panday, the United States promised to better identify
deportees and the charges against them. It also pledged to send
deportees back on commercial flights instead of charters when
possible. Immigration officials in many countries have complained
that the unscheduled charter planes dump deportees on them without
warning.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Trinidad agreed to issue travel papers within five
working days for inmates who have documents proving their
Trinidadian citizenship. For those without proof, immigration
officials agreed to investigate and issue papers within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Jamaican Attorney General Arnold Nicholson said the United
States also should fund adjustment and training programs for the
deportees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope to move beyond the Trinidad agreement and get the U.S.
to finance the rehabilitation of these criminals that it returns to
Jamaica,'' Nicholson said. He said the United States sent 1,359
convicts back to Jamaica last year.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the two-day meeting, the countries issued a
15-point statement pledging to share draft anti-drug legislation,
consider creation of a regional center to share intelligence and
set standards for seizing property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 2125 </TRAILER>
