<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge fines bridge painting company over lead exposure by employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) - A bridge painting company has been ordered to
pay a criminal fine of $210,000 for falsifying reports to make
employees' lead blood levels look legally acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Damalos Inc., a Tarpon Springs company, sent five bogus
laboratory reports to the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health
Administration in November 1998, investigators said. The results
had been altered so the lead levels appeared to meet federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The reports showed workers had lead paint levels ranging from
six to 29 micrograms of lead per deciliter of whole blood,
according to a plea agreement. However, the workers tested at
levels from 45 to 73 micrograms, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA regulations require employers to take action if levels
reach 40 micrograms or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Had OSHA known, it would have required the painters be
temporarily sidelined, said George Tragos, attorney for the company
located about 35 miles northwest of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a situation where the company thought it was helping
to keep its people employed,'' Tragos said. None of the Damalos
workers suffered any ''documented injury'' as a result of the
exposure, he maintained.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge James D. Whittemore ordered the fine Monday
and placed the company on three years probation, but said he would
not require officers to check in with probation, unless OSHA
reported a problem.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA and the FBI investigated last year after OSHA received a
complaint that a Damalos worker had lead poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The fine ordered by Whittemore was higher than federal
sentencing guidelines, but the judge agreed with prosecutors the
amount was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The conduct of the defendant presented a potential danger to
the community through its work force,'' Whittemore said.
</P>
<P>
   Damalos &AMP; Sons Inc. - an associated but separate corporation -
earlier agreed to pay OSHA $290,000 in fines by Jan. 1 for two
other regulatory cases involving lead exposure, Tragos said.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are owned by Tony Damalos.
</P>
<P>
   Lead poisoning can cause sterility or kidney failure and can
damage a person's central nervous system. In severe cases, lead
poisoning can cause death.
</P>
<P>
   In April, OSHA proposed additional fines of $456,000 when
Damalos &AMP; Sons was cited for knowingly exposing workers to
potentially fatal falls while they worked on a New Jersey Turnpike
bridge project.
</P>
<P>
   The citations resulted from an investigation into complaints
that the company's 13 employees at the bridge were working 40 feet
over water on suspended platforms without safety harnesses or
lanyards to protect them from falls.
</P>
<P>
   Damalos &AMP; Sons does bridge sandblasting and painting throughout
the eastern United States, OSHA said, and employs about 50 workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scouts appeal exclusion from state charity deduction program  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY HILL, Conn. (AP) - The Boy Scouts of America on Tuesday
urged the state to continue allowing government workers to
contribute to scouting through payroll deductions.
</P>
<P>
   A state human rights panel ruled that the group's ban on
homosexual troop leaders made it ineligible for the payroll
deduction plan. But the Scouts argued Tuesday that other groups
still in the deduction program limit participation to specific
populations.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments before the Connecticut State Employee Campaign
Committee came a day after the Irving, Texas-based Scouts and one
Connecticut scouting council filed a federal discrimination lawsuit
against the state.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Bridgeport, names
as defendants the employees' campaign committee and state
Comptroller Nancy Wyman.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are hundreds of charities that cater to a specialized
group,'' said attorney Daniel Schwartz, citing organizations for
gays, minorities and the elderly. ''We're not suggesting they're
doing anything wrong. All we're asking is that the Boy Scouts have
the right to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1910, the Scouts have an oath and law that long have
required members to promise to be ''clean'' and ''morally
straight.'' But no written rule specifically addresses
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The state Commission on Human Rights and Opportunities
unanimously ruled last month that the Boy Scouts could not be
included in the employee contribution campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the CHRO declined to rule directly on whether
the Boy Scouts' policy violates state anti-discrimination laws. But
it did find that including a group with such a policy on the
employee contribution list violated state anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committee had asked the CHRO for a ruling in
November after the New Jersey Supreme Court found the Boy Scouts'
policy was unconstitutional. The Boy Scouts appealed, saying they
had a right to free association under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey case is now before the U.S. Supreme Court and the
CHRO is awaiting that ruling before issuing one of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said that until the CHRO or another Connecticut court
rules the Boy Scouts' policy violates state law, excluding the
group from the contribution list would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committee has 20 days to rule. Separately, U.S.
District Court Judge Warren Eginton is expected to conduct a
hearing on the lawsuit Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committee hires the United Way to collect the
deductions. But the state has the right to prevent the fund-raiser
from giving the Boy Scouts any contributions not designated for a
particular agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 campaign, $9,950 was contributed directly to the Boy
Scouts by state employees. The Scouts also received a portion of
$200,000 in undesignated contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Pokorny, Scout executive of the Connecticut Rivers Council
in East Hartford - the state's largest Boy Scout council and a
co-plaintiff in the lawsuit - said the amount of money is not the
issue. The concern is that the state's ruling could open the door
for other groups to withhold money from the Scouts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state ruling does not prevent the United Way from giving the
Scouts money collected outside the state employees' campaign. But
the United Way of New Haven stopped giving funds to the Scouts in
1994 because of the policy.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller Nancy Wyman said the lawsuit was expected.
Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who represents state
employees, said he was seeking a temporary resolution while the
Supreme Court case is pending. One solution might be to place the
scouting money in a separate account until the high court rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 2144 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0177 </DOCNO>
