<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers in Sierra Leone Clash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. peacekeepers clashed with
Sierra Leone's feared rebels near a strategic bridge in the West
African country, U.N. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 rebel fighters made three attempts Monday night to
cross Rokel bridge, 45 miles east of the capital, Freetown, U.N.
spokeswoman Hirut Befecadu said. They were repelled each time by a
Jordanian U.N. battalion stationed at the bridge, which is on the
road leading toward rebel-controlled eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels were believed to have suffered casualties, but no
U.N. troops were hurt or killed.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, pro-government forces said they repelled a rebel
attack Monday at the key front-line town of Lunsar, 45 miles east
of Freetown. Two pro-government soldiers were killed and four rebel
fighters captured, an army statement said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lunsar was retaken by government forces twice last week, nearly
a month after the rebels first captured it.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front rebels killed tens of thousands
of civilians and systematically maimed many more during Sierra
Leone's eight-year civil war. They signed a peace accord with the
government last summer but reignited the conflict in early May,
seizing about 500 U.N. hostages and advancing toward the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages have since been released, and a ragtag coalition of
pro-government forces has been pushing the RUF away from Freetown.
But more than 200 U.N. personnel remain surrounded in the eastern
rebel stronghold of Kailahun, and a new group of about 21
peacekeepers has been detained in nearby Pendembu.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian doctor who visited the 21 peacekeepers Monday reported
that all were in good health and that supplies were reaching them
regularly, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.N. Children's Fund reported Tuesday that a
pro-government militia handed over a group of 138 children -- 92
young combatants and 46 children separated from families during
recent fighting -- to UNICEF and the Catholic charity Caritas
Makeni.
</P>
<P>
   The 92 child combatants had fought on the side of the Civil
Defense Force, a pro-government militia. UNICEF said Monday's
handover was the first since President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah urged
that all children under the age of 18 be demobilized.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters will be cared for in a UNICEF-sponsored Interim
Care Center until their families can be traced and reunifications
arranged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 2200 </TRAILER>
