<HEADLINE> Officials urge improvements to fatal U.S. border crossing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) - After two fatalities in six months, New
York officials are calling for major improvements to the border
crossing with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Plattsburgh-North Country Chamber of Commerce President Garry
Douglas and a chamber delegation was in Washington, D.C., Tuesday
to push a $23 million plan for full refurbishment of the Champlain
border crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The officials delivered a letter to the Canadian Embassy to
express their condolences for the second death of a Canadian
attributed to the backed-up truck traffic at the northern New York
border. They apologized for what they called the American failure
to provide the resources and attention needed to keep the border
safe as traffic increases.
</P>
<P>
   The facility was built in 1967 and uses the technology of 1975,
according to a new video Douglas unveiled Monday. It will help the
delegation present its message.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber-led ''Port of Excellence'' campaign, just six months
old, has already succeeded in obtaining about $2 million in federal
money to make interim fixes at the border.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thats a remarkable indication of the impact were having,''
Douglas said. ''But we arent going to settle for the quick fix.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Customs Agent Thomas Keefe, on hand to represent Customs
employees, said the border bottleneck is hurting the employees'
ability to look for narcotics and other illegal items.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they process one truck every minute, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
