<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Nears Vote on Education Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans batted down Democratic efforts to
add funds for schools and biomedical research to a $339.5 billion
measure financing next year's education, health and labor programs
as the House moved Tuesday to the brink of a final vote on the
year's biggest spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   With a promised veto by President Clinton waiting in the wings,
Republicans were hoping for House passage on Wednesday of a bill so
controversial that it hasn't come to that chamber's floor since
1997. The measure would boost spending for education and many other
programs over this year's levels but has prompted an election-year
fight by proposing to cut Clinton's plans for hiring teachers and
job training for adults and teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   In a bipartisan compromise, Democrats were allowed to offer and
debate several amendments aimed at restoring some of the money,
funds they would get by trimming the GOP's proposed tax cuts. But
the House parliamentarian -- controlled by Republicans -- ruled the
amendments out of order for procedural reasons and votes on them
were not taken, sparing politically difficult votes for moderate
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Democratic leaders were eager for the vote on final
passage, which they believed could hurt some Republicans in this
fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''For three years the public hasn't had an opportunity to figure
out who's where'' on this bill, said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis. ''And
we're determined to let them find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee's subcommittee that wrote the bill, said Democrats were
trying to make ''a political point'' with their amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats want ''to get people to believe the majority party
isn't supportive of special education or funding for biomedical
research'' or Pell grants, he said, adding, ''We have been the
champions in each of those areas. You have been the followers.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic amendments included proposals to add $1.7 billion for
the National Institutes of Health, $1 billion for hiring and
training teachers, $1.3 billion for school construction and $1.5
billion for special education.
</P>
<P>
   Though Republicans were against adding money to the bill,
lawmakers of both parties did not want to cut it, either. In a
measure of the measure's popularity, they voted 236-186 against
cutting every program by 0.62 percent -- a total $500 million
reduction -- to fit the measure into the budget.
</P>
<P>
   With their slim 11-seat House majority, GOP leaders spent much
of the day trying to nail down enough votes to ensure passage. Amid
absences by some Republicans and likely defections by others, party
leaders postponed a vote on final passage until at least Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders were most worried about moderate Republicans,
whose districts tend to favor spending for social programs. But one
moderate GOP lawmaker said he would probably vote ''yes'' because
with the Senate version of the bill $4 billion higher, he believed
the final bill would have more money in it.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's been the pattern year after year,'' said Rep. Sherwood
Boehlert, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also voted 313-109 for an amendment by Rep. Bernard
Sanders, I-Vt., aimed at requiring pharmaceutical companies to
charge reasonable prices for drugs they developed with the help of
federally financed basic research.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the House bill would spend about $24 billion more than
last year but nearly $9 billion below Clinton's request.
</P>
<P>
   It would provide $39.6 billion for the Education Department,
$1.6 billion above this year but $2.9 billion below Clinton's
proposal. It would ignore Clinton's request for $1.75 billion for
helping communities hire teachers, but set aside the same amount
for teacher hiring and training -- if a separate bill setting up
that program becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   It would also eliminate Clinton's $1.3 billion proposal for
repairing schools and add $1.7 billion to Clinton's $18.8 billion
request for biomedical research at the National Institutes of
Health. The Democratic amendment would have increased the amount of
money for the NIH in the bill by another $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also trim Clinton's proposals for student mentoring,
Head Start, child care grants to states, substance abuse treatment
and prevention and several job training programs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also bar the government from issuing
regulations later this year aimed at preventing workplace injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
