<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Says It'll Quit Israel Gov't  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak's key coalition
partner, the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, announced Tuesday it would
quit his government, throwing Israel once again into political
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   If Barak's 11-month-old government falls, it would paralyze
Middle East peacemaking for months. But similar crises with Shas,
which represents Israelis of Middle Eastern origin, have been
resolved before.
</P>
<P>
   Shas spiritual leaders, furious over Barak's refusal to hand
over additional millions of tax dollars for their bankrupt school
system, instructed the party's ministers to hand in their
resignations at the next Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he would use that time to persuade Shas to stay and
save the broad based government he believes is essential to
pursuing his peace policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The door is still open, if only a crack,'' he told Channel Two
television. ''I am leading a divided people, and I prefer brotherly
love to unfettered hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a message relayed by his office said Barak reserved the
right to fire the renegade ministers whenever he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   If the Shas ministers quit -- or if he fires them before Sunday,
which is also an option -- he would have to decide between calling
new elections or trying to patch together a new coalition team. His
coalition options would be to make up with Shas, to approach the
right-wing Likud opposition, or to form an even shakier minority
government.
</P>
<P>
   If Barak opts for elections or is forced into them,
Israel-Palestinian peace talks would fall off the agenda during a
campaign that might last five months or more. The two sides are
aiming to complete a peace treaty in September.
</P>
<P>
   Barak took office in July 1999 and his coalition problems
started almost immediately, with Shas threatening resignation as
early as December.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's parliament, like its people, is split along several
lines: over terms for peace with the Palestinians and Syria, over
the role of religion in daily life, and over economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's One Israel party has only 26 seats in the 120-seat
parliament. Shas has 17, meaning it holds the balance of power
between hawkish and dovish factions and can hold Barak hostage to
its demands.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Barak has solved similar Shas threats by pacifying
the party through last-minute talks. A spokesman for the Shas
rabbis said the door is still open for negotiations with Barak.
However, Shas chairman Eli Ishai gave a different message, saying
''the decision is final.''
</P>
<P>
   An attempt by Barak to rule with a narrow coalition would prove
unsuccessful, said Labor Party lawmaker Eli Goldschmidt.
</P>
<P>
   ''My prediction is that we shall have a narrow coalition but
only for six months or 12 months, and then we will have to go to
elections,'' Goldschmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Shas set up its own school system, emphasizing
religious instruction and offering long school days and free
lunches, an attractive enticement to the Shas target constituency,
made up largely of Israelis low down on the socio-economic scale.
</P>
<P>
   The school system is plagued by huge deficits and mismanagement.
The system's director was suspended under a cloud of fiscal
impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   Shas charges that its pupils receive less state money than
others. But Education Minister Yossi Sarid, Shas' nemesis, refuses
to sign over any more money unless it is accompanied by stricter
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid is the leader of the secular Meretz party, an ideological
rival of Shas. The Shas spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadiah Yosef, has
compared Sarid to the biblical villains Haman and Amalek, both of
whom tried to destroy the Jewish people, and Yosef is now being
investigated for possible incitement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel cannot be governed like this, says Meretz lawmaker Naomi
Hazan, a professor of political science.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time has come to realize that we made an experiment and it
failed,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 2219 </TRAILER>
