<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Refugees Grows Worldwide  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Conflicts in Kosovo and East Timor and
wars across Africa sent 7 million people fleeing their homes last
year, bringing to 35 million the number of people worldwide who are
uprooted and in need of protection, a leading refugee organization
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Committee for Refugees said more people were living in
refugee camps and makeshift housing at the end of this decade than
at the start. In 1990, 29 million people were either refugees --
defined as people forced to flee their countries -- or internally
displaced residents who leave their homes but not their countries
to escape fighting or political instability.
</P>
<P>
   ''The end of the 20th century has not brought an end to the
bloodshed and persecution that force people to run for their
lives,'' said Bill Frelick, policy director for the
Washington-based non-governmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   The group's World Refugee Survey 2000 found that more and more
often, people aren't crossing borders to escape. Instead, they are
staying in their own countries, albeit outside their homes and
communities. Such ''internal refugees'' accounted for 4 million of
the newly uprooted in 1999, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   That trend has prompted calls -- most vocally from U.S.
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke -- for the U.N. refugee agency to make
caring for internally displaced people more of a priority. Such
people are not afforded the same protections and care as refugees
under the Geneva Conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Committee for Refugees report found that the bulk of
the world's uprooted are in Africa -- an estimated 13.7 million.
Sudan alone accounts for one of every nine of the world's uprooted
people, with 4.4 million out of their homes, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   The group compiles its figures based on a host of information,
including government statistics, non-governmental reports, U.N.
statistics and its own field evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.refugees.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
