<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Kicks Off Campaign Tour  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Asking Americans, ''Are you better off than you
were eight years ago?'' Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore
claimed credit for the nation's roaring economy Tuesday and
proposed tax credits and trust funds to ensure better times still.
</P>
<P>
   ''America has done well. But I'm here to tell you, you ain't
seen nothing yet,'' the vice president told a foot-stomping,
hand-clapping crowd of supporters in a tiny auditorium at the New
York Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   The address opened a three-week ''progress and prosperity tour''
designed to improve the vice president's standing against
presumptive Republican nominee George W. Bush. A poll this week
showed voters slightly favoring Bush as the man they trust to
protect the economy, a worrisome sign for Democrats who have long
assumed the issue would be their strongest suit.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of this boom happened by accident,'' Gore said, giving
credit to the Clinton administration and the American work ethic.
The vice president, who has gone to great lengths at times to
distance himself from President Clinton, declared, ''I intend to
build even higher on the foundation of the Clinton years.''
</P>
<P>
   With the government expected this month to increase its estimate
of budget surpluses, a new campaign issue is taking shape: how to
divide the spoils of a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore argues that Bush's tax-cut plans would endanger Social
Security and education, health care and environmental programs.
Bush, the two-term Texas governor who has held a slight edge over
Gore in state and national polls, says tax cuts are fiscally sound
and a moral imperative when surpluses abound.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't spend money that we don't yet have on a huge tax cut
our economy can't afford, in ways that could end our prosperity and
progress,'' Gore said in his address. He referred to Bush once, and
then only as ''the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said, ''There was a lot of talk
about trust and trust funds, but the only thing Al Gore trusts is
the government. Apparently, Al Gore doesn't trust individual
Americans to make their own choices about retirement, health care
needs, education and finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Promising details as the tour continues, Gore said he will
support targeted tax cuts allowing middle-class Americans to pay
college tuition, buy health insurance and save for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated his plan that would dedicate Medicare payroll
taxes to the entitlement program and pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed tax-free, voluntary retirement accounts that
would be funded out of budget surpluses. Bush wants to use payroll
taxes, now dedicated to Social Security, for a program allowing
Americans to invest in the stock market for their retirement
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a Social Security plus, it is not Social Security
minus,'' Gore said in a slap at Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's initiative sounds similar to a proposal Clinton has put
in his budget the past two years for tax credits to encourage
savings -- a proposal Congress has not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also said he would set aside unspecified
portions of the surplus to create separate trust funds to be used
only for education, health care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that promise would be hard to keep.
</P>
<P>
   There are already more than 100 trust funds in the federal
budget, most of which are routinely tapped by Congress to pay for
programs outside the trust funds' original mandates.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a practical standpoint, (trust funds are) meaningless in
the sense that Congress can do with the money anything it wants,''
said Robert Reischauer, president of the liberal-leaning Urban
Institute and former director of the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stanley Collender, who monitors the budget for the
consulting firm Fleishman-Hillard, said the trust funds would ''put
additional pressure on the president and Congress to spend the
money as planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides believe the proposals will help crystallize their
basic economic argument: Voters can have a big tax cut or new
domestic spending, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual late-night event Tuesday after continuing on to
Scranton, Pa., Gore appeared at an airport rally timed to get him
featured on the local TV news. Addressing an enthusiastic crowd of
several hundred, Gore said: ''Are you ready to fight to win this
election?
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of small ''Progress'' and ''Prosperity''
signs posted behind Gore's head and a larger-than-usual press
corps, the ballyhooed battleground state tour didn't look much
different from the standard fare.
</P>
<P>
   The first leg will last just three days before Gore takes the
Father's Day weekend off. He spends almost as much time in New York
-- a Democratic state that isn't yet in contention -- as he does in
the battleground states of Pennsylvania and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Four-day work weeks are scheduled for the rest of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   By organizing a political trip around a single slogan, Gore is
acknowledging Bush's success at pounding home campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has divided the campaign into two-week
segments since wrapping up the GOP nomination, sticking to a single
topic for each period: education, foreign affairs, Social Security
and government reform. The tactic has given voters, most of whom
are paying little attention to the campaign, an easy script to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of the day, Gore stopped Tuesday at a Manhattan
construction site between campaign events. ''Keep up the good work,
guys,'' he shouted to a group of union workers.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Drago, a 62-year-old foreman, said these are prosperous
times for the union and its workers. But who gets the credit?
</P>
<P>
   His answer summed up Gore's problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''I give it to Clinton,'' Drago said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
