<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bowman Unsure on Red Wings Return  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Scotty Bowman shows no signs of slowing down, yet
he still hasn't made a decision as to whether he'll return as the
Detroit Red Wings coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman will be busy this summer, volunteering at the U.S. Open
golf tournament, helping NHL coaches form an association, watching
Wimbledon and attending the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   At some point he'll let the Red Wings know his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he's getting closer to making his decision,'' general
manager Ken Holland told The Oakland Press of Pontiac on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Holland and Bowman have spoken regularly by phone but do not
have plans to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, who turns 67 in September, has been waiting for a
final consultation with his doctor after a full physical last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the biggest issue is to make sure I'm on the right
page on the medical exam,'' Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman is leaving Wednesday for the U.S. Open, where he'll help
provide player updates to a centralized scoring system.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings expect to find out after the tournament whether Bowman
will return for his eighth season with the Red Wings and a record
29th NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not urgent, but I'd like to know within the next week,''
Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman would also like to meet with Holland within a week to
discuss the Red Wings' standing offer.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the subject of retirement speculation since having
knee-replacement surgery and an angioplasty that caused him to miss
the early part of the 1998-99 season. Bowman said he will not
return unless he gets a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the Wings would like to know his plans before the June
24-25 entry draft. If Bowman decides to step aside, Holland can
begin scouting for potential replacements at the selection in
Calgary
</P>
<P>
   Already a member of the Hockey Hall of Fame, Bowman has coached
eight teams to Stanley Cup titles, and is the winningest coach in
NHL regular-season (1,144) and playoff (205) history.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman is one of only two coaches in the four major sports to
win a championship with three different teams (Montreal,
Pittsburgh, Detroit).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-13-00 2240 </TRAILER>
