<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic Convention Draws Near  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic Party officials continue to cast
plans for their upcoming national convention in a positive light,
despite a fund-raising shortfall and labor dispute that could lead
to a strike by workers who keep the meeting site functioning.
</P>
<P>
   The local host committee must collect $35.3 million in cash and
in-kind contributions before the Aug. 14-17 convention at the
Staples Center here. The Democratic National Convention Committee
needs $18 million of that in cash, but the host committee has only
taken in about $11.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers played down concerns about the fund-raising Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be honest, I think the fund-raising thing has a been a
little overblown. ...All of the money that we've needed so far has
been there,'' said Rod O'Connor, chief operating officer of the
Democratic National Convention Committee. ''The money is going to
get done.''
</P>
<P>
   The host committee has raised $31.7 million, but more than $20
million has been in-kind contributions, meaning it must exceed its
original goal to come up with the needed cash.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the two committees expressed optimism that the
recent hiring of veteran Democratic fund-raiser Terry McAuliffe as
chairman of the national committee will help organizers reach the
fund-raising goal. McAuliffe was to arrive in Los Angeles on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials led about 350 media representatives on
tours of the convention site on Monday and Tuesday and did not
mention the problems that threaten to mar the event.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Wednesday, workers with the Operating Engineers
Union are to vote on a contract described as their employer's
''last, best and final offer'' in negotiations that have lasted for
months. The engineers are responsible for heating, cooling and
lighting at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only union with workers at the arena that has not
reached a contract, and thus has not signed a labor
union-Democratic National Committee peace agreement ensuring no
strikes by convention workers. Union officials declined to comment
on what would happen if the workers rejected the contract, but a
strike is considered a possibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
