<HEADLINE> IU Professor Takes Leave of Absence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- An Indiana University professor who is
one of basketball coach Bob Knight's most outspoken critics says
harassment and threats have forced him to take an unpaid leave of
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be here in the fall. It's going to cost me
financially, but I'm so exhausted, I want to get out of town,''
English professor Murray Sperber told SportsLine.com on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he opted for unpaid leave so he would not have to stay
in Bloomington. He would not say when he plans to return.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated attempts by The Associated Press to contact Sperber at
home Tuesday were unsuccessful. A university spokesman did not
return a phone message left at his home seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomington police Sgt. Scott Oldham said police are
investigating reports that Sperber received threats against his
life in retaliation for his comments to the media.
</P>
<P>
   The university recently suspended Knight for three games in the
2000-01 season and fined him $30,000 following an investigation
into accusations he choked a player in 1997. He also faces a
''zero-tolerance policy'' that will lead to his immediate firing if
he crosses the line again.
</P>
<P>
   Sperber, 59, an author of three books on college sports, has
criticized the university for being too lenient on Knight through
nearly three decades of the coach's controversial behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to continue and continue,'' Sperber said recently.
''This is a horrible hit for the image of the university.''
</P>
</TEXT>
