<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, June 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Convicted in Xerox Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- A Xerox copier repairman was convicted of murder for fatally
shooting seven co-workers in the state's worst mass murder. Jurors rejected the
insanity defense for Byran Uyesugi. He faces up to life in prison. Hawaii does
not have the death penalty. The defense did not dispute that Uyesugi, 40, shot
and killed the seven Xerox Corp. employees on Nov. 2, but he pleaded innocent by
reason of insanity. Prosecutor Peter Carlisle acknowledged that Uyesugi suffers
from a serious mental illness, but said he was aware his actions were wrong and
killed out of anger.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Nears Vote on Education Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans batted down Democratic efforts to add funds
for schools and biomedical research to a $339.5 billion measure financing next
year's education, health and labor programs as the House moved today to the
brink of a final vote on the year's biggest spending bill. With a promised veto
by President Clinton waiting in the wings, Republicans were hoping for House
passage tomorrow of a bill so controversial that it hasn't come to that
chamber's floor since 1997.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pope Attacker Arrives in Turkey
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy on Tuesday pardoned the Turkish gunman who tried to kill
Pope John Paul II in 1981, and he was immediately delivered to authorities in
Turkey -- taking with him the answers to the mysterious assassination attempt.
Despite the pardon, Mehmet Ali Agca must now serve time in Turkey for a killing
that took place before the attack on the pope. He arrived at Istanbul's Ataturk
International Airport early Wednesday. Police backed by armored personnel
carriers blocked off the gate where he landed, CNN-Turk reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Assad Buried in Home Village
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   QARDAHA, Syria (AP) -- After a day of frenzied mourning, solemn prayers and a
bit of politicking, Syrian President Hafez Assad was laid to rest Tuesday in the
mountains where he began his climb to power. Bashar Assad, the president's
oldest surviving son and heir apparent, was jostled at the head of the coffin as
clerics, elderly men in business suits or the traditional dark cloaks and white
headdresses of Alawite Muslims, and even soldiers pressed forward. ''His death
is a national catastrophe,'' said Hafez al-Shuraiqi, 69, a former schoolmate of
the president.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Accused Teen Killer To Plead Innocent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A 13-year-old middle school student charged
with killing a favorite teacher will plead innocent at his arraignment next week
on murder charges, his lawyers said today. Nathaniel Brazill, jailed under an
indictment alleging murder with a firearm, has been charged with the wrong
crimes, lawyer Robert Udell said after the teen's first appearance in court
today. A tentative arraignment date was set for June 19.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court To Hear Microsoft Appeal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said today it would hear
Microsoft's appeal of a sweeping breakup order imposed for antitrust violations.
But the government may still be able to bypass that court in favor of a direct
hearing before the Supreme Court. Government attorneys filed their expediting
request late today. The circuit court said because of the case's ''exceptional
importance'' it would hear the Microsoft's appeal with all seven eligible
judges. This would skip the normal three-judge hearing, followed by a full court
rehearing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Airline Chiefs Make Case for Merger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairmen of US Airways and United Airlines, seeking
the largest merger in aviation history, told a House committee today that the
deal would benefit consumers, but lawmakers expressed skepticism. US Airways
Chairman Stephen Wolf said the combination is ''pro-consumer and
pro-competitive.'' But members of the committee, especially those from smaller
airline markets, were not so sure.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday on profit-taking in light
trading. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 152.25 points, or 0.90 percent, to
16,762.70 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 57.63 points to 10,621.84 at Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq
composite index gained 83.15 points to close at 3,851.06.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tigers Maul Blue Jays 16-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Bobby Higginson highlighted a rare Detroit power surge with a
pair of three-run homers and seven RBIs as the Tigers bombed the Toronto Blue
Jays 16-3 tonight. Juan Gonzalez and Brad Ausmus also homered for the Tigers,
whose 59 homers rank them next to last in the AL. Higginson was 4-for-4 before
being replaced in the fifth. Tony Batista had a two-run homer, his 15th, for
Toronto.
</P>
