<HEADLINE> Giordano makes it official, he'll challenge Lieberman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) - Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano is
making it official, he will run for U.S. Senate against incumbent
Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano, a Republican, planned to launch his campaign with a
series of stops around Connecticut on Wednesday, including an
appearance with Gov. John G. Rowland in Hartford. Rowland had
earlier advised Giordano not to run against Lieberman, who won his
last election by more than 350,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been mentioned as a possible running mate for Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano, a three-term mayor, can remain in office until at
least January 2002.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say that even if he loses a statewide campaign
against Lieberman he could heighten his profile in the state
Republican Party and increase his chances for other potential
campaigns down the road.
</P>
