<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 women come forward; questions surround police handling  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Two days after a roving mob terrorized at least
16 women - including four tourists - in Central Park, questions
arose Tuesday about how authorities handled the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Two victims said police were slow to respond to their cries.
Ironically, more than 900 officers were assigned to patrol the park
that day because of a parade on adjacent Fifth Avenue. On a normal
Sunday, 36 officers patrol the 840-acre park.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir brushed off the incidents as ''isolated.'' On Tuesday, their
tone softened.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very concerned about the women who got assaulted, maybe
more than you, because I feel responsible,'' Giuliani told
reporters. ''We regret very much that this has happened. Sometimes
some sick, crazy criminal or drunk kids do sick things.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the ''sick and shocking and horrible'' incidents
will be investigated ''with tremendous enthusiasm and enormous
force.''
</P>
<P>
   The incidents involved men spraying water on women, tearing at
their clothes, groping them and, in some cases, robbing them.
Although perhaps as many as 40 men took part, only two were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   At their bail hearing Tuesday, prosecutors related the ordeal of
an 18-year-old British tourist. She and her friends were surrounded
and soaked with water; men tore at her shirt and ripped off her
shorts; hands violated her private areas. Then the men were gone,
fleeing into crowds of people in the park seeking relief from the
90-degree weather.
</P>
<P>
   The woman quickly found two cops who helped her search for her
attackers. Minutes later, two men were arrested: the wrong men,
defense lawyers claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt that they were under a lot of pressure to arrest
somebody,'' said David Kapner, attorney for David Rowe, 24, of
Hempstead, on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting incidents and murders are on the rise in the city, a
contrast to dramatic declines in the 1990s. Relatively little crime
has occurred this year in Central Park, but that was no comfort for
victims of Sunday's rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Bryant, 29, a kickboxing teacher in Manhattan, was inline
skating near Central Park South and Sixth Avenue when the group of
men set upon her, trying to pull down her pants. Bryant struggled
and the men ran off.
</P>
<P>
   ''I skated over to an officer and told him I was attacked and
that the crowd was out of control,'' Bryant said. ''I told him I
was assaulted, but he acted like it was nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant approached two other officers who told her to file a
report at the Midtown North Precinct. She did, but no one offered
to help her look for her attackers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, the mother of one of two Long Island teen-agers
attacked, said police also ignored her daughter's cries. They only
pointed to an ambulance parked nearby, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Police are conducting an internal investigation into the
complaints, and Giuliani said if the allegations are true, the
officers will be ''severely disciplined.'' The mayor offered a
$10,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction
of any of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   All the attacks occurred during a short span of time, around 6
p.m. and in the southern portion of the park, near the zoo and the
Plaza Hotel. Among the victims were a French couple on their
honeymoon, the three British tourists and an Associated Press
reporter and her friend.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said police officers were not nearby when the specific
incidents occurred.
</P>
<P>
   While some victims criticized the police, the French couple
praised them, the husband told the AP in a telephone interview
Tuesday. After the attack, the couple ran to an officer, who put
them in his car. The couple was surrounded by about 100 people, 10
to 20 of whom attacked them, the husband said. Some of the crowd
ran after them, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''He took us in his car to protect us from the crowd,'' said the
man, who did not want his name or his wife's to be used.
</P>
<P>
   The officer radioed for help, and within minutes, the husband
said between 50 and 60 cops on scooters and in cars arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The officers asked if the couple could identify their attackers,
but the husband said, ''We weren't ready to do that at that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   The husband added that when the group first surrounded him and
his wife, he thought it was a joke. He also said there were several
people snapping pictures and videotaping them.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, police were working with several television stations
to obtain amateur videotape of the attacks that was aired during
Monday and Tuesday newscasts. Police hope to identify some of the
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Ludwig, attorney for defendant Tremayne Bain, 23, of
Brooklyn, said the group his client and Rowe were with have given a
videotape to police that shows the defendants were not involved in
the attacks. Police did not immediately comment on Ludwig's
assertions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tape corroborates the fact that they were about 150 yards
away when the attack (on the British tourists) took place,'' Ludwig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe and Bain were charged with second-degree aggravated sexual
abuse, first-degree sexual abuse and second-degree robbery. Bail
was set at $10,000 for each, and both were still in jail Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man said anything during the brief hearing, and they did
not enter pleas. They are due back in court Friday. Rowe and Bain,
who are friends, had come into Manhattan to watch the Puerto Rican
Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attacks, Central Park was crowded as usual on Monday
and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Central Park is my oasis away from the big city,'' said Claire
Duane, 34, of Manhattan. ''We can't let thugs like this take away
our refuge, our sense of well-being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-13-00 2330 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000613.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MacArthur Foundation Awards Grants  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE ZIEGLER DIZON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- An architecture professor who helps design
innovative buildings in poor communities and a scholar in black
American photography were selected Tuesday as two of this year's 25
winners of $500,000 MacArthur ''genius grants.''
</P>
<P>
   The academics, artists, activists and scientists chosen by the
John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation will each receive the
money in no-strings-attached funding over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ''My high school transcripts and my Auburn University
transcripts are proof that I'm no genius, but I'm smart enough to
take the money,'' said Samuel Mockbee, who teaches architecture at
Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Mockbee, 55, of Canton, Miss., was chosen for his work with the
Rural Studio, a project at Auburn that he co-founded in 1992. The
studio, in Newbern, Ala., is in the middle of one of the nation's
poorest areas.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the Rural Studio design houses, churches and other
community buildings on a limited budget. Past projects have
incorporated discarded tires, bottles and even hay.
</P>
<P>
   A secret process is used to determine the MacArthur grant
winners. Recipients cannot apply, but rather are selected by
hundreds of anonymous nominators. A 13-member selection committee,
also anonymous, then makes recommendations to the foundation's
board, which makes the final picks.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Willis, curator of exhibitions for the Center for
African-American History and Culture and the Anacostia Museum at
the Smithsonian Institution, said she was shocked by her selection.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've worked in isolation for so long,'' she said. ''I never
really realized that somebody was taking note of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis, 52, of Washington, recently began showing her own
photographs, which focus on women at work and the black female
body.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners include Ben Katchor, a 48-year-old New York
cartoonist who draws a weekly strip on urban life called ''Hotel &AMP;
Farm.'' Katchor has also published several books of comic art that
reinvent New York history.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Munoz, a 37-year-old vice president with the National
Council of La Raza, a Hispanic civil rights organization, was
picked for her lobbying efforts on immigration and civil rights
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest recipient among this year's fellowship winners was
Hideo Mabuchi, a 28-year-old assistant physics professor at the
California Institute of Technology. He has studied the relationship
between microscopic systems, such as atoms, and the tools used to
measure and examine them.
</P>
<P>
   He said hopes to use the grant to develop the creative side of
science education.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: MacArthur Foundation:
http://www.macfdn.org/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
