<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-13 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suharto Family Talking With Govt.  </HEADLINE>
By PAMELA SAMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Indonesia's president said Tuesday that family
members of former autocratic President Suharto are negotiating with
the government to return any alleged ill-gotten gains from the
years of Suharto's rule.
</P>
<P>
   The family ''would like to give back the fortune ... to the
state,'' President Abdurrahman Wahid said during a speech to the
American Indonesian Chamber of Commerce in New York. He said
negotiations are under way.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's family and lawyers could not immediately be reached
for comment, but negotiations between the government and Suharto's
family would be a significant development in a possible corruption
case against the former Indonesian leader. Wahid has said he is
willing to pardon Suharto for any wrongdoing if the ex-leader
returns illegally acquired riches -- a statement he repeated
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, 79, ruled Indonesia with an iron fist for 32 years
until riots forced him from office in 1998. He is now the top
suspect in a scandal involving the misuse of millions of dollars by
several charitable foundations controlled by his family during his
reign.
</P>
<P>
   Though Suharto continually denies any wrongdoing, his foes
accuse him of stashing much of the money overseas and using the
rest to build huge business empires for his six wealthy children.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Suharto refused to cooperate with a state graft
investigation on the grounds of ill health -- family members and
defense lawyers claim a series of strokes have left him weak and
sometimes incoherent, with dangerously high blood pressure and
mental blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated and skeptical by what they claimed were stalling
tactics, prosecutors placed the ex-leader under house arrest on May
29 and compelled him to answer questions. Indonesia's attorney
general said last week that he is confident of building a solid
corruption case against Suharto by midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, who was elected president last year, has said he wants to
fight endemic corruption in Indonesia, reform the economy and
improve the climate for overseas investors. He reaffirmed those
commitments Tuesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has pledged to give private enterprise the leeway to
operate, Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will encourage the private sector,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid is in the United States primarily for medical treatment --
he is nearly blind from a progressive eye disease. But he also met
with President Clinton in Washington on Monday and emphasized
Indonesia's commitment to reform.
</P>
<P>
   He told Clinton that achieving progress is a matter of
give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to stress exports and investment,'' Wahid said he told
Clinton. ''I asked the United States to assist us by opening its
doors to our goods.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he asked Clinton to help Indonesia wipe out corruption
and achieve the goal of a ''clean government in Indonesia as soon
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Jakarta set up a high-level committee to combat
corruption. The move follows a string of scandals, including the
Suharto case and one that implicated several former top government
officials in a scheme to funnel money illegally to former President
B.J. Habibie's presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
